commit_message:
Fix problem 'MCollective agents didn't respond within the allotted time'

- increase mcollective retries for puppet queries;
- decrease frequency of puppet state report via mcollective.

Change-Id: I61302e33deb68ace8e5f1d7980a099a2c300b215
Co-Authored-By: Dima Shulyak <dshulyak@mirantis.com>
Closes-Bug: #1356954

Add rate limiting per tenant

Add rate limiting per tenant per single node,
or per gunicorn worker in gunicorn enabled configuration

Implements blueprint: rate-limit-per-tenant

Although this change doesn't work for horizon, it should be okay for other clients that use this functionality.  

Horizon Django objects, such as tables and views, seem to support the prev / next URL's, and contain flags such as "has_more_data".  The cinder REST API's return a next URL when there's more data, although there's a small bug with that right now (bug #1350558).  

I think in addition to this change, we might need a new cinderclient interface that returns any prev / next URL links in addition to the collection of volumes.

commit_message:
Support pagination for volume list

Since v2 api supports pagination, we should add this support in
cinderclient too.

Change-Id: I9d4cb9e192523c14cf7df043deabe156dbb8e216
Closes-bug: 1325773

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-21 01:33:05.000000000', 'message': 'Add missing flags to fakelibvirt for migration

Commit 26504d71ceaecf22f135d8321769db801290c405 added
VIR_MIGRATE_UNDEFINE_SOURCE and VIR_MIGRATE_PEER2PEER
to the live and block migration default flags but did
not add those flags to the fakelibvirt module for
testing.

This change adds the missing flags and also adds
VIR_MIGRATE_NON_SHARED_INC for block migration which
was also missing.

Change-Id: I5f3af95a56b95ec20f93b12360bf8b3d40b5f45f
Closes-Bug: #1359475
'}]
commit_message:
Add missing flags to fakelibvirt for migration

Commit 26504d71ceaecf22f135d8321769db801290c405 added
VIR_MIGRATE_UNDEFINE_SOURCE and VIR_MIGRATE_PEER2PEER
to the live and block migration default flags but did
not add those flags to the fakelibvirt module for
testing.

This change adds the missing flags and also adds
VIR_MIGRATE_NON_SHARED_INC for block migration which
was also missing.

Change-Id: I5f3af95a56b95ec20f93b12360bf8b3d40b5f45f
Closes-Bug: #1359475

commit_message:
Set rgw host to short hostname

The radosgw init script on CentOS checks the short hostname
with the one defined in /etc/ceph/ceph.conf. If these don't
match radosgw won't be started.

Change-Id: I215284c0ea24ac4469132c0e34f51bba8357b717
Closes-bug: #1348730

commit_message:
Add link to /root/.cephdeploy.conf -> /etc/ceph/ceph.conf

ceph-deploy requires that its local config file (previously $(pwd)/ceph.conf)
is exactly the same as /etc/ceph/ceph.conf on the system or --overwite-conf
has to be specified. Since we need to manipulate it and can't guarantee order
 from Puppet / Ruby we just link to two on the primary-controller to avoid
 the issue.

All additional users of config should config pull with --overwite-conf and
not have this issue.

The old link is left in place at this time to support older versions of
 ceph-deploy and can be removed in a later release.

Closes-bug: #1333814
Change-Id: I0b61c71effcf779801756968b8ed8b8cb93cb54b

commit_message:
Add python-zaqarclient to global-requirements

After the rename, a new version of zaqarclient has been released. This
commit adds the library to the global-requirements but keeps the old
marconiclient, which would likely be used for stable branches. It'll
remove once it's completely obsolete.

Change-Id: I27d4ea6180e849e5098ece6f3ba580d422be38a2

commit_message:
Set python hash seed to 0 in tox.ini

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but nova unittests don't currently pass
with a random hash seed so set it to the python default seed.

This change will allow us to use new tox again and remove the
restriction on tox<=1.6.1 to run unittests.

Also see Ib54364877a251db48c54dfdc43c503281ea1f04a.

Change-Id: I8834487e8c7bcdbeae8397c1a10a18873976ce61
Partial-Bug: #1348818

commit_message:
Properly handle driver specification in connection URLs

If optional database driver is specified in connection URL,
DriverManager fails to find corresponding driver unless we trim that
from the scheme name before passing it into stevedore.

blueprint enable-mysql-connector

commit_message:
Align ActionQueue rsyslog params in templates

The changes accepted in fix should be aligned
with other templates we use for client.conf and
server.conf then installing and configuring rsyslog.

Related-bug: #1339659

Change-Id: I9108b0fb992f3dd5a68f3b9d39d78705e243d9fb
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

Switch from /etc/init.d/mysql bootstrap-pxc to
/etc/init.d/mysql restart-bootstrap when bootstrapping
a new cluster. This ensures that, even when Percona starts

bootstrapped.

Change-Id: Ia720e40329a1d39db2e25fc917fbf5b5ea85dedc
'}, {'created': '2014-05-09 16:55:22.000000000', 'message': "Fix percona multi node clustering

* Switch from /etc/init.d/mysql bootstrap-pxc to
  /etc/init.d/mysql restart-bootstrap when bootstrapping
  a new cluster. This ensures that, even when Percona starts
  at boot, that new config is loaded and the cluster is
  bootstrapped.

* When relying on Heat metadata and OS:Heat:SoftwareDeployment,
  we can't guarantee metadata is available upon the first
  os-collect-config run. So, ensure BOOTSTRAP_NODE and MY_HOST
  have values before continuing.

* Ensure we don't touch the initialized file if percona fails
  to bootstrap or restart.

commit_message:
Improve percona cluster initialization

* Switch from /etc/init.d/mysql bootstrap-pxc to
  /etc/init.d/mysql restart-bootstrap when bootstrapping
  a new cluster. This ensures that, even when Percona starts
  at boot, that new config is loaded and the cluster is
  bootstrapped.

* If percona fails to bootstrap or restart, ensure we do not
  touch the initialized file, allowing os-refresh-config to
  try again on the next iteration.

Co-Authored-By: Gregory Haynes <greg@greghaynes.net>
Change-Id: Ia720e40329a1d39db2e25fc917fbf5b5ea85dedc

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-20 18:38:58.000000000', 'message': "Fix license check for NetApp driver

According to the NetApp API documentation the 'license-list-info' call
returns an array with element type 'license-info'. This element type
doesn't have an element with the name 'package' which leads to an
exception.
Use the name 'service' to get the license name and check with element
type 'is-licensed' if the license is available.

Change-Id: Ib14b28aae50a4c1135b02d6c2db296479c75f8c2
Closes-Bug: 1359207
"}]
commit_message:
Fix license check for NetApp driver

According to the NetApp API documentation the 'license-list-info' call
returns an array with element type 'license-info'. This element type
doesn't have an element with the name 'package' which leads to an
exception.
Use the name 'service' to get the license name and check with element
type 'is-licensed' if the license is available.

Change-Id: Ib14b28aae50a4c1135b02d6c2db296479c75f8c2
Closes-Bug: 1359207

commit_message:
Fix variable name in api/v<n>/snapshot.py

Noticed in a recent bug fix that the when the show
method was copy/pasted at some point the variable name
vol was not updated.

Silly annoyance, but thought I'd go ahead and replace vol
with snapshot to make the variable name reflect what's
actually in use here.

Change-Id: I137ecc4987258450e93195cfed5e128063b92914

commit_message:
Fix bootstrap issue on Volume Backup Details page

There is a large empty area in the middle of the Volume Backup Details
page. This submit fixes that problem.

Change-Id: If0fa4231e8761986208f7c1104866b549b9d99f7
Closes-Bug: #1350502

[{'created': '2014-05-29 16:31:08.000000000', 'message': 'Wait for ssh demon to become active

With only a single SSH host key being checked, devtest attempts to connect to
the seed really quickly. Although devtest does wait for the node to become
pingable, this is not long enough for sshd to fully wake up on slow hosts.

This patch makes devtest wait until it can definitely ssh to the seed before
initialising Keystone.

Change-Id: Ibfd20bf632cdf3381615dad68ecf620685553d5f

'}, {'created': '2014-06-12 11:12:38.000000000', 'message': 'Wait for os-collect-config to complate on the seed

Currently in devtest we wait for a node to become pingable and then
start configuring the seed details. However the node may not have
completed its configuration as os-collect-config may still be running
on the seed node, configuring low level services. This means we can
start configuring services too early and fail to correctly configure
the seed.

As the seed image carries local metadata and it is therefore not
under Heat control, we need to listen for and send a completion
signal. This allows us to detect when the seed has completed
configuration and the jumphost can safely continue.

Change-Id: Ibfd20bf632cdf3381615dad68ecf620685553d5f

commit_message:
Wait for os-collect-config to complete on the seed

Currently in devtest we wait for a node to become pingable and then
start configuring the seed details. However the node may not have
completed its configuration as os-collect-config may still be running
on the seed node, configuring low level services. This means we can
start configuring services too early and fail to correctly configure
the seed.

As the seed image carries local metadata and it is therefore not
under Heat control, we need to listen for and send a completion
signal. This allows us to detect when the seed has completed
configuration and the jumphost can safely continue.

Requires for CI: Ib52efa0f3f7c26d00fee7c14ffad6a812766dd0d
Change-Id: Ibfd20bf632cdf3381615dad68ecf620685553d5f
Closes-Bug: #1329528

commit_message:
Track object version relationships

This adds another developer "helper trap" for inter-object version
dependencies. If an object that another object depends on is bumped
in version, this test will note the change and remind the developer
(or reviewer) that the parent needs a version bump and backport
rule added.

Change-Id: Ia81d034f850173401cd84a79b15ae0f7c80b9653

commit_message:
Allow passing user_id to v2Password plugin

Whilst this is undocumented it is supported by keystone and relied upon
by other services.

Change-Id: Idf8be75e2e0b275d9c9840082079100dd13a70ff

commit_message:
Link to ml2_conf.ini

If installed from package the neutron openvswitch-agent is started with
--config-file /etc/neutron/plugins/openvswitch/ovs_neutron_plugin.ini

Change-Id: I096cf0b42f9db3ef844f632d187648fe12341990

commit_message:
Update theme for docs

The current developer docs theme used is out of sync with the other
openstack projects. This patch will update the docs to provide a more
consistent look and feel when using developer docs

Change-Id: I4a59f194bd0fc8c86c6d3c6b8cadb839a5158935

Textarea of height 10 lines seems large considering the usecases
in Horizon for forms containing multiple fields. Reducing it to a
lesser value for subnet workflows in networks and images forms.

Change-Id: I99dc6f735ed446ff4005aac7a981461c236f65b9

commit_message:
reduce the height of the textarea to 4

Textarea of height 10 lines seems large considering the usecases
in Horizon for forms containing multiple fields. Reducing it to a
lesser value for subnet workflows in networks and images forms.

Change-Id: I99dc6f735ed446ff4005aac7a981461c236f65b9
Closes-Bug: 1358856

commit_message:
Shelve should give guests a chance to shutdown

Currently in libvirt operations which power off an instance such as stop,
shelve, rescue, and resize simply destroy the underlying VM. Some
GuestOS's do not react well to this type of power failure, and so it would
be better if these operations followed the same approach as soft_reboot
and give the GuestOS as chance to shutdown gracefully.

This is one of a set of changes that will eventually expose the choice
of whether to give the GuestOS a chance to shutdown via the API.

This change implements the compute manager changes to shelve.

Partially-Implements: blueprint user-defined-shutdown
DocImpact

Change-Id: Iec3dfd17725440958aac395ebc471e51afd6522e

commit_message:
Remove unused network parameter from _allocate_ips_for_port

I found this in the context of a patch that I was reviewing [1].  I
found that patch left a few loose ends and so I thought it would be
better to remove the parameter as a separate refactor so that it can
be carefully reviewed.  The other patch [1] should be rebased to this
one.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/100963

Change-Id: I75115fa46ea3340ef0f13feb28ad2cdb0387fed7

commit_message:
Expand arp_responder help text

Add additional text to arp_responder help to ensure that
proper documentation is included in the configuration guide.

Make ML2 and L2population references consistent.

Closes-Bug: #1321320

Change-Id: I0fc0691fc3729aa39888c90ca871ad7f711343f8

[{'created': '2014-05-06 00:18:15.000000000', 'message': "A service to install diskimage-builder

Enabling service 'dib' will install the following repos:
* diskimage-builder
* tripleo-image-elements
* os-collect-config
* os-refresh-config
* os-apply-config

These repos are already pre-fetched in devstack-gate.

This will facilitate gating on changes in these projects by building
a custom image then running the heat-slow job against that image.

Since this service only installs repos it can be enabled by default.

Change-Id: Ia911cdee86f5b2e2ba1557e5aa8bf392b92ef555

These repos are already pre-fetched in devstack-gate.

This will facilitate gating on changes in these projects by building
a custom image then running the heat-slow job against that image.

diskimage_builder is pip installed from the current git checkout
if the dib service is enabled. This allows devstack gating on
diskimage-builder changes while also allowing diskimage-builder to
be installed from releases for other scenarios (for example, ironic).

Change-Id: Ia911cdee86f5b2e2ba1557e5aa8bf392b92ef555

commit_message:
A service to install diskimage-builder

Enabling service 'dib' will install the following repos:
* diskimage-builder
* tripleo-image-elements
* os-collect-config
* os-refresh-config
* os-apply-config

These repos are already pre-fetched in devstack-gate.

This will facilitate gating on changes in these projects by building
a custom image then running the heat-slow job against that image.

diskimage_builder is pip installed from the current git checkout
if the dib service is enabled. This allows devstack gating on
diskimage-builder changes while also allowing diskimage-builder to
be installed from releases for other scenarios (for example, ironic).

Change-Id: Ia911cdee86f5b2e2ba1557e5aa8bf392b92ef555

commit_message:
Unsort pbr and hacking in requirements files

Each of these wants to come first. Python does not have a dep solver,
so order is actually important.

Change-Id: I10450de1839c41d729b606a04a944507d2427987

commit_message:
Extend the docstring for obj_make_compatible() with examples

This adds to the docstring for obj_make_compatible() to help outline
the rules and scenarios to help developers understand what they need
to do in that method, and when.

Change-Id: Ifa8cb9a4f9a1a4d5afd0da4629a7d476a52c62d6

commit_message:
Create authentication specific routes

These routes are purely based on your current authentication and bridge
the gap between what is available in the standard identity-api for
fetching scope targets based on user_id and what is required for the
federation APIs.

Implement /auth/projects /auth/domains and move /catalog to
/auth/catalog

Change-Id: I464c0ca5cc9f250d593340e9563de45b077dd4cd
Implements: blueprint auth-specific-data

commit_message:
Install heat-cfntools and heat-templates repos

These projects contain agents which can be installed on custom
images. Installing these repos will allow a future change to
build a custom image containing these projects. This will allow
gating on any changes in these projects by running heat-slow
on the custom image.
The corresponding devstack-gate change is
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/92055/
Change-Id: I7b1343c094f755f79ddeb1bac3ff4c0daa3fb70c

commit_message:
Allow LDAP lock attributes to be used as enable attributes

Some LDAP servers support disabling accounts via a boolean "lock"
attribute. For these servers, a value in LDAP of "True" means that
the account is locked, while a value of "False" means the account
is active. When the "user_enabled_mask" and "user_enabled_emulation"
options are not in use, Keystone currently expects a boolean
"enabled" attribute where "True" means the account is enabled and
"False" means the account is disabled.

To support LDAP account lock attributes, we need a way to tell
Keystone that the boolean values from LDAP are inverted. This
adds a new "user_enabled_invert" setting that allows the enabled
boolean logic to be inverted in the resource (LDAP), while leaving
the logic as-is in the model (Keystone user object).  The existing
default behavior remains as-is.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I2a89d4b98c854e68e1bb10f53b8b29d92f945f60
Closes-bug: #1337029

This is still failing the virtual-ironic job -- which is mostly stable at this point.

From looking in the logs, it appears the problem is that nova-compute was started 35 seconds before ironic-api, leading to n-cpu failing during init.

This is recorded at the following bug but hasn't been a problem for this job so far. It showed up in other testing.

https://bugs.launchpad.net/ironic/+bug/1309548

The fix for this problem is to have nova-compute use that class. However, nova doesn't support out-of-tree compute managers....

commit_message:
Ironic and baremetal install diskimage-builder with pip

This change installs diskimage-builder with pip instead
of from git, and only if the executable ramdisk-image-create
isn't already installed.

This allows the ironic and baremetal to consume the latest
release of diskimage-builder by default, and gives the option of
defining version constraints for which version to install.

If the dib service is enabled (which it isn't by default) then
diskimage-builder will already be installed from git and will
not be re-installed for ironic and diskimage-builder.

Change-Id: Ic6613a11e2c4fb7a1261b81cdc2cf958515e60cd

[{'created': '2014-07-29 14:27:56.000000000', 'message': 'Use a FakeRequest object to test middleware

swift was being imported to provide a blank Request
object but very little of the functionality in that
object was being used. FakeRequest provides the
bare minimum funcionality required:

* REQUEST_METHOD
* PATH_INFO
* wsgi.input based on cStringIO
* custom header manipulation

Depency on swift tarball removed.

Closes bug: 1285388

Change-Id: If0fbb8f00765ac915e5b426a3661492f4b4df9f4
'}, {'created': '2014-07-30 08:47:46.000000000', 'message': 'Use a FakeRequest object to test middleware

swift was being imported to provide a blank Request
object but very little of the functionality in that
object was being used. FakeRequest provides the
bare minimum funcionality required:

* REQUEST_METHOD
* PATH_INFO
* wsgi.input based on cStringIO
* custom header manipulation

commit_message:
Use a FakeRequest object to test middleware

swift was being imported to provide a blank Request
object but very little of the functionality in that
object was being used. FakeRequest provides the
bare minimum funcionality required:

* REQUEST_METHOD
* PATH_INFO
* wsgi.input based on cStringIO
* custom header manipulation

Other functionality from swift has either been
duplicated or replaced:

* InputProxy (which counts bytes of request bodies)
  has been duplicated.
* logging uses common log functionality
* path_split does straight string splits for the desired results

Note that these changes do nothing to change functionality nor
anything to address the performance concerns being evaluated
and discussed elsewhere.

Closes bug: 1285388

Change-Id: If0fbb8f00765ac915e5b426a3661492f4b4df9f4

commit_message:
Honor volume:get policy

The fix for bug 1356368 hard-coded a policy check (same as
rule:admin_or_owner) for volume:get.  While in most cases this is
what people want, it'd be good we honor policy setting.

Note that before commit 0505bb268942534ad5d6ecd5e34a4d9b0e7f5c04,
DB query volume_get() actually acted as the policy checker for
volume:get, and it raised VolumeNotFound if context.project_id didn't
match volume['project_id'].  The check_policy() in volume:get didn't
get a chance to raise PolicyNotAuthorized exception.  So in this
change we keep the same behavor.

Change-Id: If43cec5cce977b9220296709b4e243b35b06ecd5
Related-bug: #1356368

commit_message:
upgrade to newer oslo.i18n

This release includes a new test fixture for writing
tests for classes that need to use both lazily and
immediately translated strings.

Change-Id: I26702ad9fef6005b12de72d0bfefed98b24a0382

generate object hash codes by setting GENERATE_HASHES in the
environment.

commit_message:
Add v3scopedsaml entry to the setup.cfg.

Since Patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/107231/ was abandoned and
entry ``v3unscopedsaml`` stays in the setup.cfg, there should
also some room for v3scopedsaml entry which lets users scope their
unscoped tokens.

Change-Id: Ie42206c323d287b905b4c5da9c790e544a8b8433

Actually as sdague pointed out we'd need a global-reqs update on this so we should make it work for both versions."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2014-08-20 15:09:55.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2014-08-20 15:13:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2

probably worth rethinking our overall testing approach here as well. Would be nice if jsonschema had a non string based way of figuring out the kind of error. Would be good upstream contribution.'}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2014-08-20 15:29:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

There are detail in jsonschema.ValidationError(attribute s'instance' and 'validator_value' probably enough to test specific case). If pass the detail down to exception.ValidationError, then we can testing those detail instead of string message."}, {'account_id': 11069, 'date': '2014-08-20 15:33:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)

As the original bug reporter, this fix works for me (cherry-picked to local environment and tested with both 2.3.0 and 2.4.0), but I have concerns about the removal of information from the assertion error exception (as compared to before) should something like this happen again.'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2014-08-20 15:34:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2

Nice change for supporting both jsonschema versions.

I prefer the message of new jsonschema library.
I felt a float value in the message seemed strange even if passing an integer value. so the problem seems to be fixed in new jsonschema library, that is nice change for me.

I don't +A because jenkins does not finish yet, but really ++ :-)"}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2014-08-20 15:36:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Corey, we still assertEqual() on the two parts (which arguably should have been that way in the first place) so you should see both the expected and actual versions of the things being examined. Am I missing something else?'}, {'account_id': 11069, 'date': '2014-08-20 15:44:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Dan Smith

Correct me if I am wrong, but because you provided your own assertion error message (ie "Exception details did not match expected") the reference and actual values are not printed.

Before:
MismatchError: !=:
reference = {'code': 400,
 'detail': u'Invalid input for field/attribute foo. Value: 0. 0 is less than the minimum of 1'}
actual    = {'code': 400,
 'detail': 'Invalid input for field/attribute foo. Value: 0. 0.0 is less than the minimum of 1'}

After:
AssertionError: Exception details did not match expected

Before it was highly informative (without requiring print statements or debugger).'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-08-20 15:51:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 11069, 'date': '2014-08-20 15:53:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

@Dan Smith

nevermind, my testing approach was incorrect previously (mucked with the re.match and assertEqual statements), but after altering the expected/reference message i see that both it and the actual message are printed.

MismatchError: !=:
reference = 'Invalid input for field/attribute foo. Value: 65536. 65536.0001 is greater than the maximum of 65535'
actual    = u'Invalid input for field/attribute foo. Value: 65536. 65536 is greater than the maximum of 65535'

commit_message:
Fix expected error details from jsonschema

The jsonschema 2.4.0 release slightly changed some of the error messages
that are provided when validation fails. This updates the unit tests to
expect the proper string and avoid failing as a result.

Change-Id: Ic8e32140e49e394659e7ebbecb28afb704b23b7c
Closes-bug: #1358881

commit_message:
Rename --timeout param to --http-timeout

The --timeout parameter was already used by the
load balancer subcommand so adding it as a top-level
parameter broke the load balancer commands. This
patch renames the new --timeout top-level command
to --http-timeout so it doesn't conflict with the
existing load balancer commands.

DocImpact

Closes-Bug: #1353536
Change-Id: I3d1dd9537e546191c5905e0aa5415de5308d9c7e

I still pushed up a patch to add the flags to fakelibvirt but that's more or less for completeness now."}]

[{'created': '2014-02-19 05:42:55.000000000', 'message': 'Enable live block migration for libvirt.

In TripleO we wanted to enable live block migration. Pleasantly
surprising was finding that all it required was better options to
libvirt.

This may require a newer libvirt than we gate on - upgrading that
is in progress, but possibly more importantly is deciding the
minimum version we require *by default*. It seems reasonable to
me to use stable released features of libvirt by default, and allow
folk to downgrade from the defaults if they want to use an old
libvirt.

commit_message:
Update migration defaults

In TripleO we wanted to enable live block migration. Pleasantly
surprising was finding that all it required was better options to
libvirt.

I'm told this works with the libvirt we gate on, though as we don't
gate migration yet, its hard to tell.

Change-Id: I7b997666474ec324c5034e3660a7271b8423bca8
DocImpact:
UpgradeImpact:

commit_message:
Manually disable IP version when creating network subnets.

In some configuration, IPv6 is not supported. This patch provides
a way to disable IPv6 by hiding the ip version drop down menu and
setting the initial value to IPv4.

Closes-bug: 1352404

Change-Id: I950a1e19d509fdf4816816dd7b0f05bd418e7147

[{'created': '2014-08-13 14:06:02.000000000', 'message': 'Fixed setting GUID on cephjournals for ubuntu

The issue was that pmanager created ceph-journal partitions (one for
every ceph-osd) but guid was set for only one ceph-journal partition.

Change-Id: I50e3edc6f22310ec2ba541d677bffe1896c28fe7
Closes-Bug: #1355342
'}]
commit_message:
Fixed setting GUID on cephjournals for ubuntu

The issue was that pmanager created ceph-journal partitions (one for
every ceph-osd) but guid was set for only one ceph-journal partition.

Change-Id: I50e3edc6f22310ec2ba541d677bffe1896c28fe7
Closes-Bug: #1355342

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V resize down exception

The Hyper-V driver does not support resize down and is currently
raising an exception if the user attempts to do that, causing the
instance to go in ERROR state.

The driver should use the recently introduced instance faults
"exception.InstanceFaultRollback" instead, which will leave the
instance in ACTIVE state as expected.

Closes-Bug: #1354448

Change-Id: Ibaf8482562094cd2b3165dc62a907fa9e0e56e19

[{'created': '2014-08-20 01:55:04.000000000', 'message': "Remove hardcoded version.

API clients generally use semantic versioning, not pbr's pre-version facility.
This line causes local package builds to have the wrong version today
(0.0.2.dev.. when 0.0.2 is already released). Furthermore pbr will in future
detect this and error. Removing the line will let pbr automatically manage
versions for you.

Change-Id: Idd75b05c8b9ce93fcb71bc46cf648a3be99e53a0

commit_message:
Remove hardcoded version

API clients generally use semantic versioning, not pbr's pre-version facility.
This line causes local package builds to have the wrong version today
(0.0.2.dev.. when 0.0.2 is already released). Furthermore pbr will in future
detect this and error. Removing the line will let pbr automatically manage
versions for you.

Change-Id: Idd75b05c8b9ce93fcb71bc46cf648a3be99e53a0

commit_message:
Set self.kwargs in horizon.tables.actions.LinkAction

Set self.kwargs during __init__ so that get_link_url no longer raises
an AttributeError at "return self.url(datum, **self.kwargs)".

Change-Id: I97aeab781ee1945c3028590be0a6a046c7fcd9b9
Closes-Bug: 1290909

commit_message:
Check on schemes not stores

Since the `_upload` method loads the store based on the scheme, we need
to check whether the scheme exists in the known schemes instead of
checking in the list of known stores. Without this fix, stores with a
scheme name different than the store itself will not be usable through
the `x-image-meta-store` header.

Change-Id: Ia33afc1629cb47a31982df7932ac0d9aeb201b4f
Closes-bug: #1357462

commit_message:
Add dib-utils to projects list

We need this to be able to use the newly split out dib-utils in
the tripleo CI jobs.

Change-Id: Iad657e7d23e5d0b37c091ca46760619c19330e1e

(10 comments)

After reading through the spec again, I felt that we could
perhaps further simplify this in its first iteration. I put the comments inline.

The key differences are (and I paraphrasing some of the offline email conversations here as well):

* I have tried to keep the minimum requirements in here such that we can potentially evolve in later iterations. I have removed most (if not all) optional details since its difficult to justify their requirement in the first iteration.

* To go with the above, the insertion operation is now a simple CRUD on the Service Interface resource.

* We dont have insertion modes (L2, L3, etc) explicitly spelt out (as Subra pointed out). I believe this can be handled as an implementation detail.

* The older service_attachment_point is now a service_interface. The former terminology had no precedence in Neutron, the latter does (also we were actually defining the attachment point as an interface, so why not call it that).

* References to attachment have been replaced with insertion (as Carlos rightly pointed out).

* Drop 'ServiceCommon' DB table and instead use 'ServiceBase' table to store that information - yes, renamed it

* Drop the 'SERVICE' resource and just stick with existing service resources - the service resource did not make sense in the way it was included here

* Add service_interfaces attribute to each existing service resource - yes

* won't it still need the optional subnet_id attribute? - what is the use case for this?

* Regarding Stephens comment on preserving the Subnet id field for FWaaS use case - I believe this should be driven by the firewall configuration. If not, we can add it later, but for now this mixes the zone semantics with insertion.

* whether we should keep the network / attachment related fields in their corresponding service objects (i.e., port/subnet attribute on LBaaS, router-name on FWaaS...etc) on phase one.  - the problem with this approach is that it is not consistent across services. Hence the orchestration entity does not have a uniform/consistent interface to invoke operations on the services when orchestrating operations like service chaining.

* why "using the Flavor id?" It will look like this spec depends on the Flavor spec. - We are still very hopeful that flavors will make it, so I think its okay to mention this, although this proposal references it only for completeness.

* In which category does the "Router Id" falls in? Is it considered a "Neutron Service? - Yes, and it does inherit for ServiceBase I believe (BobM can confirm).'}, {'account_id': 9375, 'date': '2014-07-18 22:12:22.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 19.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-18 22:12:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 19:

commit_message:
Add spec for service-base-and-insertion

Add the specification for the serviceBase class and
service insertion to allow neutron services to be
inserted explicitly in addition to the default insertion mode.

Change-Id: I595d7fe224f49f8cbc4203569d7862deaa74e1e7

commit_message:
document "vCenter full scale HA support"

- describe how service behave on failure in Multi-node HA mode
- update screenshot in Reference Architecture which shows that
  nova-network and nova-compute can run on distinct controllers
- add limitation about security groups which are not support by
  nova-network with vCenter
- add limitation that vCenter 5.1 and later are supported
- add limitation about that we cannot select in which vCenter cluster
  virtual machines are started
- remove limitation about sparse HA support
- rename flatDHCP to FlatDHCP

Change-Id: I1b238334caf524e7c903d74de59282c4e1f5978d
Implements: blueprint vcenter-documentation-update-fuel-5.1

commit_message:
Latest tox should work for openstack now, use it

Remove the tox pin that was in place to avoid issues with tox 1.7.0 and
1.7.1. Latest tox (1.7.2) is compatbile with openstack's tox.ini files
again and should work with tempest. This change is self testing and will
confirm this.

Making this change is important so that devs can stop worrying about
package version pins and helps ensure we don't get left behind by
upstream.

Change-Id: Ibf2102d6ad439dd354ae687f7aafec9ceca6cf9c

commit_message:
Have the memory backend provide a lock to storage

To be a little more consistent when in-memory backends
are shared have the memory backend provide the storage
backend a lock instance that is shared among all storage
backends that are associated with the same flow detail.

Change-Id: Iec276148ba9288bad52a47edbda1f0c5042d7ce9

commit_message:
Disable H803.

As long as a repo agrees not to care about a period or not, there is
no reason to gate on it. And this rule is just wasting resources, and is
easy to miss if you don't run flake8 after you make the commit.
(http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-June/037480.html)

See
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-June/010850.html

commit_message:
Merge from oslo-incubator

Merging processutils.py and dependencies from oslo-incubator.
Primarily, I want change d6b55fb but the rest come along for
the ride.

0d7296f Add kwargs to jsonutils.load(s) functions
3310d8d update new requests logger to default WARN
33afb20 Fix broken formatting of processutils.execute log statement
3d90045 Backport code for i18n to check lazy at runtime
433fa0b Make logging_context_format_string optional in log.set_defaults
4d9328c Python 3: enable tests/unit/test_log.py
5fd77eb Ability to customize default_log_levels for each project
6751b30 Remove extra whitespace
726d00a Adjust oslo logging to provide adapter is enabled for
ac92c06 Add default log level for websocket
cb5a804 Move `mask_password` to strutils
d6b55fb Remove `processutils` dependency on `log`
e184dd3 Fix exception message in openstack.common.processutils.execute
ef37e03 Added missing jsonutils.dump() function

Change-Id: I567f514faed5a8467602257d35a98625801daf22
Closes-Bug: #1349890

commit_message:
Fix handling of deprecated opts in CLI

Deprecated opts are supposed to be accessible via the CLI in a similar
way as they are available via CONF. Currently these values are ignored.

Add CLI flags for all the deprecated opts as well.

Change-Id: If5f23c7b30a0cacda893a5e3150bc6bdb95f3693

commit_message:
Remove lxml as a forced depend

keystoneclient only needs lxml for saml support, which is an
optional contrib piece. Since keystoneclient is massiely used, and
as lxml is a big beefy depend that requires C compilers, move
lxml to test-requriements.

Change-Id: I01b6b702fb8f414884cb1da306d5b95406e86513

commit_message:
Exposed fixed VIP address to Heat ControlFixedIPs parameter

When an SSL certificate is used to secure the overcloud,
its common name will dictate the IP address that should be
used for the cluster VIP managed as a Neutron port.

This change recognizes when the PUBLIC_API_URL is set
(via a shell argument to devtest_overcloud.sh) and builds
a JSON string to be provided to Heat via the ControlFixedIPs
parameter.

Change-Id: Icb23248b7bd5347a5cac78403a702b321316bc9c

subject: Make sure to release the floating ip afterwards

We use semantic versioning, not pbr's pre-version facility. This
line causes local package builds to have the wrong version, and
pbr will in future detect this and error.

Change-Id: Ia625d31e87d137e867badcdeac1f33630257bb8c
"}]
commit_message:
Remove hardcoded version.

We use semantic versioning, not pbr's pre-version facility. This
line causes local package builds to have the wrong version, and
pbr will in future detect this and error.

Change-Id: Ia625d31e87d137e867badcdeac1f33630257bb8c

pbr pre-versioning causes current sdist to have too-low versions if

commit_message:
Fix bigswitch setup.cfg lines

Bigswitch was not correctly creating the bigswitch/ssl/ca_certs and
host_certs directories when running the setup.py install step.  This
makes it difficult to correctly package the plugin because it has
missing files/directories.

Fixes bug 1358982

Change-Id: I78c6e96887340ea90494ed9e109b3b7fda6653c9

commit_message:
Remove hardcoded version.

We use semantic versioning, not pbr's pre-version facility. This
line causes local package builds to have the wrong version, and
pbr will in future detect this and error.

Change-Id: I3f4504ac2e9c49fd1bba964999e789d7a6e918bf

commit_message:
Added option --advance-by to allow advancing of lease start date

Added option --advance-by to the mutually exclusive group containing
--defer-by to allow the user to advance the start date of a lease.

Change-Id: I4cb801e29407917f3d409a7866bd53ec2184e93d
Closes-Bug: 1314791

commit_message:
Replacement mox by mock

Replace mox testing library by mock one in:
- glance/tests/unit/common/test_rpc.py,
- glance/tests/unit/test_filesystem_store.py,
- glance/tests/unit/v1/test_registry_client.py,
- glance/tests/unit/v1/test_upload_utils.py,
- glance/tests/unit/v2/test_registry_client.py

Partially Implements: blueprint replace-mox-with-mock

Change-Id: Idbdec5a23d88cee22e9045d43739bfa09b6b4523

Could you quickly explain how you prevent anyone on the local system from running rootwrap ? At first glance, once the daemon is started, it accepts commands from any local user. The current rootwrap limits potential root escalation to the specific user the service runs under."}, {'account_id': 708, 'date': '2014-03-21 10:38:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I didn't find any special filtering for users that run rootwrap. I think it's only limited by sudoers.

If you could run rootwrap as usual then and only then you can run rootwrap daemon. Upon startup daemon provides calling process with socket path and a key that is needed to do RPC calls. It pushes the data to stdout that should be connected directly to calling process through pipe.

More details are here: https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/rootwrap-agent"}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-03-21 11:37:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: No score

(2 inline comments)

Thanks for the explanation.

I'm generally concerned with the additional complexity of the security model here. Rootwrap used to be pretty simple, with sudoers being in control of the escalation. The sudoers rule would do access control (right user, right process, right config file). In your case after the initial setup, the security model all relies on the token, which means we have to audit the security of *that*. For example, is it possible for another process to snoop on that token ?

Separate question: Do you have an example of what the changes to the consuming project would look like ? I'm trying to see where the decision of using daemon mode should live (neutron config ? rootwrap config ?)

Also see inline comments"}, {'account_id': 708, 'date': '2014-03-21 12:26:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: (2 inline comments)

We bypass checking all the same rules for every command that one (only one) service process runs using sudo.

Token is securely passed to calling process through a pipe. Noone but kernel can intercept it. Afterwards it is stored in calling process' memory and cannot be retrieved from it by other processes. (if you have process memory isolation hole you're screwed anyway)

>Separate question: Do you have an example of what the changes to the consuming project would look like ? I'm trying to see where the decision of using daemon mode should live (neutron config ? rootwrap config ?)

I don't have examples of usage for this in different projects yet. I plan to work on Neutron integration now.

I currently see it as an option in Neutron config like 'use_rootwrap_daemon' that will cause service to use rootwrap's Client to run commands as root. The problem with testing is that we need to test interpreter shutdown process. We need to spawn child process that would run client, spawn rootwrap process and then die. We'd expect it to shutdown rootwrap process. commit_message:
Add an option to run rootwrap as a daemon

Benchmark for daemon mode is to be added in next commit.

Current results on my machine for 'ip a':
        method          :    min       avg       max       dev
                   ip a :   3.701ms   4.966ms  12.720ms   1.206ms
              sudo ip a :  11.531ms  13.538ms  19.685ms   1.525ms
sudo rootwrap conf ip a :  92.253ms 119.431ms 211.236ms  17.948ms
     daemon.run('ip a') :   6.718ms   9.914ms 189.873ms  18.201ms

Implements: blueprint rootwrap-daemon-mode
Change-Id: Iace26738f910a18a5d1d3479fad949027e5a3816

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V unit test path separator issue

Fixes an issue in a unit tests were path separators were not
handled in a platform independent way causing the test to fail
on Windows.

Change-Id: Ifca77a561e5a95af8655f2373af665292b2ca3cb
Co-Authored-By: Zsolt Dudas <zdudas@cloudbasesolutions.com>
Closes-Bug: #1358702

commit_message:
labs: add osbash/shutdown.sh symlink

The recent changeset that added an "osbash shutdown.sh" line to
config/scripts.* was missing the symlink that makes the line work.

This patch adds the necessary symbolic link to the repo.

Change-Id: Ife4e1e2cbe2cca8c2eda34e5432c81db6284a24f

commit_message:
VMware: Update Datastore with more fields

This patch adds two new fields 'accessible' & 'type' to the Datastore.
Accessible defines a state where the Datastore is reachable to the compute host.
Type defines the type of datastore e.g VMFS, VSAN etc.

Co-Authored-By: Sabari <smurugesan@vmware.com> (see I2c71df9adb68c12f4be0648cae98d10e53787ace)

Change-Id: I5a7e723fa36b1860efe53a7feb40b9b2f27e8a25

commit_message:
change CryptoPluginManager to be instantiated in the module scope

Fixes an issue where SecretStore was repeatedly creating new instances
of the stevedore extension manager, which caused issues with the loaded
plugins.

Closes-Bug: 1358386
Change-Id: Icfafce0ec6fbacc2c39e23ea31f200a56197b7cb

commit_message:
parse order independent dependency on ceph::pool

ceph class is evaluated by Puppet parser before cinder::volume::rbd, so
at the eval time Class['cinder::volume::rbd'] is not defined and the
dependency was not declared.

Change-Id: I4c07a9a9c3037e5e98f60e17bd916b20b7269d85
Closes-Bug: #1352335

commit_message:
return power state ERROR instead of an exception

iboot's _power_status() could raise an exception if it doesn't get the
expected response from the iboot command. A new IBootOperationError is raised
if the response isn't a list, and we return ERROR power state if the returned
list doesn't have the power status information.

Change-Id: I4b88c24a77a4f46464cf36224878b4e3205f646c
Partial-Bug: #1267693

commit_message:
Add new checklinks tox environment

This is a new non-voting job that will be used for changes of the
manual. It checks that URLs in the manual are reachable and valid.

commit_message:
Turn verbose/debug logging off by default

There's a lot of logging with either verbose or debug,
so much so that error messages generated by misconfigured
data sources can be hard to find.

This change makes debug/verbose False by default.

Change-Id: Ia3571f50b7dca51722a8a7a62468a40cc77dd7c1

commit_message:
Tweak to README to use 'password'

This change suggests using 'password' when installing devstack
so that they don't need to modify the data source configuration file.

Change-Id: I86985985ef2a26543c8425c437a98926913d2ef8

commit_message:
Removed unused column

Previously, the first column in the neutron:networks table
was not defined; hence, it always held the value "None".

This change eliminates that column from the neutron:networks table,
moving all the columns ahead by one, positionally.

Change-Id: I21527c1b2fa848a69539480d918810a592224cdf

commit_message:
Properly surface rule errors to API

Previously, any syntax errors generated when adding a new rule
to a policy would result in the user seeing an Internal Server Error.

This change catches syntax errors and rethrows them using the Exception
class caught by the API and returned to the user.

Change-Id: I4cbe4fef402ff80556f499b0ec7d676623b19d52
Closes-bug: 1356619

commit_message:
Fixed devstack installation to handle datasource config

A recent commit changed the datasource configuration but
failed to update the devstack installation procedure
to reflect those changes. In particular the installation
should copy a sample datasource configuration into
/etc/congress and set the appropriate variable in the config file.

This change includes both fixes.

Change-Id: I1cd99f109c1eb27dfb63d90ea353dcac2f8edb7e

commit_message:
Removed Services theory

Previously, we relied on the Services theory to hold
datasource configuration information.  A recent commit
changed where that information was stored but neglected
to remove this theory.

This change removes it.

Change-Id: I1916dd5a05a6bba04501c487242ef5305ff7cb0f

commit_message:
Make strutils.mask_password more secure

Make some enhancements to strutils.mask_password to allow it to catch
more cases of passwords in strings. Test cases have been added to test
for these newly added situations.

The following is a listing of patterns that will be handled. The
keyword that mask_password uses (a list of four now) is represented by
<key> and the password is shown as <password>. Quotes (both single and
double) are represented as <quote>.

--<key> <password>
--<key> <quote><password><quote>
<key> = <password>
<key> = <quote><password><quote>

All existing tests and patterns are still handled.

Originally-submitted-in: If5ea2d91b1d87c995f50d07a1281879493bd7adb

Change-Id: I928fabc1fb6c8a0f76dc349fba232fcbeb3046a0
Partial-Bug: #1345233

Make strutils.mask_password more secure

Make some enhancements to strutils.mask_password to allow it to catch
more cases of passwords in strings. Test cases have been added to test
for these newly added situations.

The following is a listing of patterns that will be handled. The
keyword that mask_password uses (a list of four now) is represented by
<key> and the password is shown as <password>. Quotes (both single and
double) are represented as <quote>.

--<key> <password>
--<key> <quote><password><quote>
<key> = <password>
<key> = <quote><password><quote>

All existing tests and patterns are still handled.

Change-Id: If5ea2d91b1d87c995f50d07a1281879493bd7adb
Partial-Bug: #1345233

[{'created': '2014-08-20 01:53:14.000000000', 'message': "Remove hardcoded version.

API clients generally use semantic versioning, not pbr's pre-version facility
which is used for the API servers. This line causes local package builds to
have the wrong version (2.0.dev.. when 2.0 was released a long time ago) and
pbr will in future detect this and error.

Change-Id: Ief099a077f0c4da656dcdba10d86531694fc8491
"}]
commit_message:
Remove hardcoded version.

API clients generally use semantic versioning, not pbr's pre-version facility
which is used for the API servers. This line causes local package builds to
have the wrong version (2.0.dev.. when 2.0 was released a long time ago) and
pbr will in future detect this and error.

Change-Id: Ief099a077f0c4da656dcdba10d86531694fc8491

commit_message:
Remove the temporary deploy element after rename

This is dependent upon change in tripleo-incubator
I1ff4bb98c99dfe87ccc4fb19767b93e27707d3a7 and concludes the
renaming of deploy to deploy-baremetal

The rename was performed so that each element had a more descriptive
name, and so that each element could accurately set an element-provides
of "deploy", given that the elements enable tripleo deploys via the
ramdisk image.

Change-Id: Ic2ca5f95b8895fa0d6d7314cab9de30a7204541c

commit_message:
Skip tests requiring platform specific features

OS X does not support loop devices like Linux does. Trying to run
those tests on OS X results in test failures.

Skip those tests on OS X.

Change-Id: I9d1d7ac8eb9dd778a765622c70ca6507d808feeb

lifeless: The tabs here are an issue. FWIW when I re-wrote ensure bridge I initially used tabs for my HERE docs as well. See the comments on patchset 1 here:

 https://review.openstack.org/#/c/69918/

While I like the indentation simple editing can become problematic given we don't have an automated style checker. Cutting and pasting things (which often removes the tabs) is also a problem.

Furthermore if we really do want to use tabs we should be consistent and use them in all the HERE docs within this file.

I won't -2 for it but I'm convinced the tabs really are a bad idea.

Other than that I think this now looks reasonable. Thanks for the fixups."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-07-08 09:51:48.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 16.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-08 09:51:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16:

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-06-30 03:30:15.000000000', 'message': "Fix issues with provider networks and public ips

The current public IP address implementation layers a VLAN access port
underneath the exterior bridge - br-ex/br-ctlplane. This prevents the
use of Neutron provider network tagging because the access port
overrides everything.

Instead, put public IP addresses in an access port on top of br-ex,
allowing provider networks to be tagged by Neutron openflow rules.

The change is backwards compatible - though the old method really is
broken so I've marked it as deprecated in the docs and the code.

We will need to change our heat templates and then incubator glue code
to use the new option before the bug can be closed.

Partial-Bug #1325114

Change-Id: I3f77f72ac623792e844dbb4d501b6ab269141f8e

commit_message:
Fix issues with provider networks and public ips

The current public IP address implementation layers a VLAN access port
underneath the exterior bridge - br-ex/br-ctlplane. This prevents the
use of Neutron provider network tagging because the access port
overrides everything.

Instead, put public IP addresses in an access port on top of br-ex,
allowing provider networks to be tagged by Neutron openflow rules.

As part of this we allow a new non-default route, so that IPMI
connectivity is not lost when the default route is put onto a VLAN.
This is only needed for the seed - the undercloud can receive this via
DHCP.

The change is backwards compatible - though the old method really is
broken so I've marked it as deprecated in the docs and the code.

We will need to change our heat templates and then incubator glue code
to use the new option before the bug can be closed.

Partial-Bug #1325114

Change-Id: I3f77f72ac623792e844dbb4d501b6ab269141f8e

commit_message:
Rescue should give guests a chance to shutdown

Currently in libvirt operations which power off an instance such as stop,
shelve, rescue, and resize simply destroy the underlying VM. Some
GuestOS's do not react well to this type of power failure, and so it would
be better if these operations followed the same approach as soft_reboot
and give the GuestOS as chance to shutdown gracefully.

This is one of a set of changes that will eventually expose the choice
of whether to give the GuestOS a chance to shutdown via the API.

This change implements the compute manager changes to rescue.

Partially-Implements: blueprint user-defined-shutdown
DocImpact

Change-Id: I296397f4fe3308be3727ec127929cea60d46b882

commit_message:
Resize should give guests a chance to shutdown

Currently in libvirt operations which power off an instance such as stop,
shelve, rescue, and resize simply destroy the underlying VM. Some
GuestOS's do not react well to this type of power failure, and so it would
be better if these operations followed the same approach as soft_reboot
and give the GuestOS as chance to shutdown gracefully.

This is one of a set of changes that will eventually expose the choice
of whether to give the GuestOS a chance to shutdown via the API.

This change implements the compute manager changes to resize for libvirt.

Partially-Implements: blueprint user-defined-shutdown
DocImpact

Change-Id: I03a52cfcc77d89e0982fcdf88be0651b3f12cbdd

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-01-24 15:50:22.000000000', 'message': "Power off commands should give guests a chance to shutdown

WORK IN PROGRESS - Currently trying a modified approach to see
if I can get the impact on gate tests down to an acceptable level

Currently in libvirt operations which power off an instance such as stop,
shelve, rescue, and delete simply destroy the underlying VM. Some
GuestOS's do not react well to this type of power failure, and so it would
be better if these operations followed the same approach as soft_reboot
and give the guest as chance to shutdown gracefully.

Even where VM is being deleted, it may be booted from a volume which
will be reused on another server.

The shutdown behavior is defined by two new configuration values:

- shutdown_timeout defines the overall period a Guest is allowed to
complete it's shutdown

- shutdown_retry_interval defines how frequently within that period
the Guest will be signaled to shutdown.  This is a protection against
guests that may not be ready to process the shutdown signal when it
is first issued. (e.g. still booting)

The default values for these may be overridden by Image properties,
allowing different types of guest OS to specify how long they need
to shutdown cleanly.

This is one of a set of changes that will eventually expose the choice
of whether to give the GuestOS a chance to shutdown via the API.

This change implements the libvirt changes to power_off() and adds
a clean shutdown to compute.manager.stop().

Subsequent patches will:
-	Add clean shutdown to Shelve
-	Add clean shutdown to Rescue
-	Add clean shutdown to Terminate
-	Convert soft_reboot to use the same approach
-	Use image propertied to override the timeout values
-	Expose clean shutdown via rpcapi
-	Expose clean shutdown via API

Partially-Implements: blueprint user-defined-shutdown
Closes-Bug: #1196924
DocImpact

Change-Id: I432b0b0c09db82797f28deb5617f02ee45a4278c

"}, {'created': '2014-06-13 11:36:55.000000000', 'message': "Power off commands should give guests a chance to shutdown

Currently in libvirt operations which power off an instance such as stop,
shelve, rescue, and resize simply destroy the underlying VM. Some
GuestOS's do not react well to this type of power failure, and so it would
be better if these operations followed the same approach as soft_reboot
and give the guest as chance to shutdown gracefully.

The shutdown behavior is defined by two new configuration values:

- shutdown_timeout defines the overall period a Guest is allowed to
complete it's shutdown

- shutdown_retry_interval defines how frequently within that period
the Guest will be signaled to shutdown.  This is a protection against
guests that may not be ready to process the shutdown signal when it
is first issued. (e.g. still booting)

The default values for these may be overridden by Image properties,
allowing different types of guest OS to specify how long they need
to shutdown cleanly.

This is one of a set of changes that will eventually expose the choice
of whether to give the GuestOS a chance to shutdown via the API.

This change implements the libvirt changes to power_off() and adds
a clean shutdown to compute.manager.stop().

Subsequent patches will:
- Add clean shutdown to Shelve
- Add clean shutdown to Rescue
- Convert soft_reboot to use the same approach
- Use image propertied to override the timeout values
- Expose clean shutdown via rpcapi
- Expose clean shutdown via API

Partially-Implements: blueprint user-defined-shutdown
Closes-Bug: #1196924
DocImpact

Change-Id: I432b0b0c09db82797f28deb5617f02ee45a4278c

be better if these operations followed the same approach as soft_reboot
and give the guest as chance to shutdown gracefully.

The shutdown behavior is defined by two values:

- shutdown_timeout defines the overall period a Guest is allowed to
complete it's shutdown.  The default valus is set via nova.conf and can be
overridden on a per image basis by image metadata allowing different types
of guest OS to specify how long they need to shutdown cleanly.

- shutdown_retry_interval defines how frequently within that period
the Guest will be signaled to shutdown.  This is a protection against
guests that may not be ready to process the shutdown signal when it
is first issued. (e.g. still booting).  This is defined as a constant.

This is one of a set of changes that will eventually expose the choice
of whether to give the GuestOS a chance to shutdown via the API.

This change implements the libvirt changes to power_off() and adds
a clean shutdown to compute.manager.stop().

Subsequent patches will:
- Add clean shutdown to Shelve

commit_message:
Power off commands should give guests a chance to shutdown

Currently in libvirt operations which power off an instance such as stop,
shelve, rescue, and resize simply destroy the underlying VM. Some
GuestOS's do not react well to this type of power failure, and so it would
be better if these operations followed the same approach as soft_reboot
and give the guest as chance to shutdown gracefully.

The shutdown behavior is defined by two values:

- shutdown_timeout defines the overall period a Guest is allowed to
complete it's shutdown.  The default valus is set via nova.conf and can be
overridden on a per image basis by image metadata allowing different types
of guest OS to specify how long they need to shutdown cleanly.

- shutdown_retry_interval defines how frequently within that period
the Guest will be signaled to shutdown.  This is a protection against
guests that may not be ready to process the shutdown signal when it
is first issued. (e.g. still booting).  This is defined as a constant.

This is one of a set of changes that will eventually expose the choice
of whether to give the GuestOS a chance to shutdown via the API.

This change implements the libvirt changes to power_off() and adds
a clean shutdown to compute.manager.stop().

Subsequent patches will:
- Add clean shutdown to Shelve
- Add clean shutdown to Rescue
- Convert soft_reboot to use the same approach
- Expose clean shutdown via rpcapi
- Expose clean shutdown via API

Partially-Implements: blueprint user-defined-shutdown
Closes-Bug: #1196924
DocImpact

Change-Id: I432b0b0c09db82797f28deb5617f02ee45a4278c

commit_message:
Ensure /etc/mysql/my.cnf removal

Additional fix to conflicting mysql config files
in order to fix mysql syslog logging in Ubuntu.
For simple deployment (custom_setup_class undef):
* /etc/mysql/my.conf should be used in Ubuntu
For HA case for Centos/Ubuntu:
* /etc/mysql/my.conf should be absent
* /etc/my.cnf should be used
(Note that changes are Fuel OSCI packaging specific)

Closes-bug: #1349601

Change-Id: I56c1b5ebca2553d341fe0498451075294f3e651f
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Edited docs to improve context

Updated versioning, added core concept definitions, modified secret description.
Moved the Secrets and Orders Examples to after the API operations info.
Added Limits section for traceability of current limits.
Removed Architecture and Service Endpoints sections as these are not
specified in other OpenStack docs or relevant to non-RAX deployments.
Made capitalization consistent for sections.

Change-Id: I45dabb16299879f8580efa5878e21e6aa0239b8e

This patch needs another rebase as it's a bit a moving target."}, {'account_id': 6072, 'date': '2013-09-25 11:17:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I have general concern about this approach.
We're moving towards having providers for services. Each provider (or plugin-driver) is a piece of code which potentially can introduce new db models.
So in order to be consistent with this approach, any plugin driver should have it's migration. 
That looks like an overkill to me, especially when it comes to admin-user experience: in order to add/remove provider to the list of providers, one will need to run migration (?) 
Something tells me that db migration is not a good way of dealing with db requirements of multiple drivers neutron may have. So far we didn't have any issues with that because anything particular implementation needed was introduced under neutron/db/ where project collects 'common' models. But pushing code to common is more difficult than having your own vendor-specific models in your driver.


Also, AFAIK, some other projects adopt opposite approach, moving from migration-only to sqla-model-generated db (and adding UTs for testing consistency of migrations and models)"}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2013-09-25 15:12:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

I am happy to abandon this patch if you have concerns with it.
Before doing that, I would kindly ask for somebody else to chime in with an opinion.

In my opinion the disadvantages of auto generation are greater of your concerns, but I am not able to prove them in an inquestionable name, so it is just my opinion.

I can add anectodal evidence of deployment left in an uncosistent state because of a mix of migrated/autogenerate schemas, but that would be pointless.

Concerning your points:
* That looks like an overkill to me, especially when it comes to admin-user experience: in order to add/remove provider to the list of providers, one will need to run migration (?) 

It's not an overkill since generating a migration is straightforward; the process is also documented. I also thought providers where now not stored anymore in the database, but I might be wrong. also, I have probably lost track of things, but I don't recall that adding a provider required a data model change.

* Something tells me that db migration is not a good way of dealing with db requirements of multiple drivers neutron may have. So far we didn't have any issues with that because anything particular implementation needed was introduced under neutron/db/ where project collects 'common' models. But pushing code to common is more difficult than having your own vendor-specific models in your driver.

A driver usually should not add/alter models. We know this is not happening as 'drivers' here are plugin/drivers hybrid or something else which is not merely a driver. I think a solution could be easily found in the migration template.
But again this is only my opinion - I can't prove it right now.


* Also, AFAIK, some other projects adopt opposite approach, moving from migration-only to sqla-model-generated db (and adding UTs for testing consistency of migrations and models)

I was under a different impression - but I have a fairly limited vision from my little world - if you could kindly point me to this projects I will be happy to look at how they're solving the problems we've witnessed with hybrid approaches."}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2013-09-25 16:31:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

enikanorov:

I actually think several openstack projects have moved in the opposite direction (from auto-generated DB schema's to manual DB migration). We had some racy issues in Glance functional tests for example (see the Glance db_auto_create config option history). Also, users would sometimes hit racy startup issues as well where DB initialization would occur before config files were fully configured (DB settings in place), migrations would fire w/ SQLAlchemy..., only to get re-executed again w/ MySQL once the services were restarted after configuration.

My preference would be to see not relying on auto-generated DB schemas."}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2013-10-09 14:43:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Thanks for the great cleanup. Populating db tables by migration is a common way across OpenStack projects and Neutron is the last part which does not use initial db migration. It is a good step. Disabling db schema auto-generation has been discussed from the previous release and everyone is taking care of db migrations during Icehouse cycle, so it is a good timing to do it.

Regarding meta plugin db migration, meta plugin need to clarify how db migrations work **both** for initial deployment and upgrade. I haven't figured out how meta plugin handles db migrations. meta plugin loads other plugins based on its configuration. How do db migrations for existing tables work? Even if register_models() works for initial deployments, I don't understand how it works for upgrade. Reverting register_models for meta plugin later is a possible option, but i believe it is not a blocking issue of this patch."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-03-26 10:31:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Works for me

One thing I still don't understand is why the quotas table needs to be added. In this patch I added it in the ml2_initial migration because the gate uses the ml2 plugin. However, I tried the linuxbridge and ovs legacy plugins and they are also missing the quotas table.

I wonder if it's devstack problem? It seems quotas are enabled by default, so devstack should run neutron-db-manage with an option to enable DbQuotaDriver? Then the quotas table would be created at folsom_initial?

Or is it because this line in neutron/db/migration/alembic_migrations/env.py:

  DATABASE_QUOTA_DRIVER = 'neutron.extensions._quotav2_driver.DbQuotaDriver'

should actually be:

  DATABASE_QUOTA_DRIVER = 'neutron.db.quota_db.DbQuotaDriver'

I don't understand at all how quotas configuration works. :("}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2014-03-26 15:10:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: No score

Henry, good catch!

quotas table migration in folsom_initial is tricky in two points: (1) it depends on configuration options and if config quota driver is used the quotas table is not created and subsequent migrations for quotas table may fail, (2) the path of Db quota driver was moved in Grizzly cycle.

Let me investigate the situation for a while.'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2014-03-26 15:42:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

I remember I filed a bug https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1277379 on quotas table in folsom_initial. I added my observation detail in the bug report.

As a conclusion According to my observation, we need to (1) change quota db driver path (as Henry pointed) and (2) remove a check of quota driver config in folsom_initial.'}, {'account_id': 6524, 'date': '2014-03-26 20:15:07.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-03-26 20:15:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

migration were updated to address this.

commit_message:
Remove auto-generation of db schema from models at startup

This patch removes the Neutron capability of creating database tables
from sqlalchemy models for all those model classes for which
a table is not found in the database schema.
Migrations should be the official and only solution for creating and
managing the Neutron db schema.
This patch also adapts unit tests in order to ensure test schemas
are still correctly created.

DocImpact
Update deployment documentation accordingly.

Closes-Bug: #1207402

Change-Id: Ie4ee5507888ecad5f6dc32ce7a029c43014687a2
Co-Authored-By: Henry Gessau <gessau@cisco.com>

commit_message:
Add remove_swift class

This class removes swift packages on Ubuntu
nodes before new swift packages are installed or
updated. This is a workaround for the broken swift
packages in 5.0 release that conflicts with other packages
durung the update.

Change-Id: I83fb7f78415309d088a6894a54a57708e8b40b91
Closes-Bug: 1356873

commit_message:
Separate ALLOWED_HOSTS and ServerAlias configuration

In some cases it is required to be possible to have different values
of parameter ALLOWED_HOSTS in settings_local.py and ServerAlias directives
in vhost.conf. This patch separated parameter $fqdn to two new parameters:
$allowed_hosts and $server_aliases.

Change-Id: I431ec01dd32e5e7c460251502dbd1c1b03ec2fe7

commit_message:
Adding tests for the barbican - key management service

This commit covers the work items 1a, 1b (partially),
2, 3a as defined in blueprint:
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/tempest/+spec/add-basic-tests-for-barbican

This commit also inclues changes to the sample tempest configuration to
include barbican configuration. By default, barbican is not
expected to be available as part of the devstack installation.

Change-Id: Ie742c44af2f39c39bbf975492856755657a55244

commit_message:
Restart containers on docker service refresh

Devicemapper bugs in docker 0.10 cause containers
to incorrectly restart when docker service is
restarted when Puppet upgrades the RPM. Added
lazy unmounts to dockerctl and a refreshonly
exec to start all containers when Docker service
is restarted (because of package upgrade).

Puppet Docker service resource tries to also
start all Fuel containers. This will show a
warning if storage containers are not yet built.

Includes bugfixes for purging iptables rules and
starting nailgun and ostf containers while nginx
container is not yet started.

Change-Id: I9c6d9b04bdaa5cf1fcc9752cc1e8f42cf693de1b
Closes-Bug: #1358144

commit_message:
Change default size for strings to 1

The valid request generator produces by default strings
with value 0, which is an empty string.

Change-Id: I9e7da4ea89faf4785ef94c435c85dc2d244f9839

commit_message:
Add upgrading alarm storage in dbsync

Currently we don't upgrade alarm storage in
ceilometer-dbsync command. This CR fix it.

Change-Id: Ie170a3a83c917c6a94f33dc2b39de1204ee946b8
Closes-bug: #1359159

commit_message:
Upgrades, add retries on first database dump

Add retries for for db dump, because
there could be cases when postgres
container didn't have time to start
and run postgres service.

Related-Bug: #1358144

commit_message:
Revert "fuel_upgrade: add KillSupervisord hook"

We don't need to kill supervisor, because
during host-system upgrade we don't restart
supervisor anymore
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/115315/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/112077/

As result when we kill container in pre-upgrade
hook, nobody runs it and upgrade fails because
we use supervisor during docker containers
upgrade.

Related-Bug: #1358144
This reverts commit 71e55fe025a38e4c734a41e2e202462f0c29e7e0.

Change-Id: I0329b5110d632ac675f7d2e12c64c9ca4ea446d3

commit_message:
Use host-upgrade.pp and keep old fuel_version

This enables docker package upgrades on host system,
which requires dockerctl to be able to restart
all containers. The switch to host-upgrade.pp
is necessary to run puppet and not break
supervisor config.

Change-Id: I2c4fa2f030cda00b456499af5d5245162714ccaf
Related-Bug: #1358144

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-05 16:51:57.000000000', 'message': 'Refactor dockerctl attach and supervisor stop

- Refactor dockerctl attach function to provide possibility to
  correctly handle SIGINT sent from supervisord during stop
  process. In order to do so we fork "docker attach" and run loop
  in order to "trap" (catch) SIGINT/SIGTERM and shutdown container
  properly
- Use SIGTERM instead of SIGINT for dhcrelay_monitor supervisor
  service, because we have "sleep 30" loop in the monitor script,
  so it will handle SIGINT only when sleep ends.
- Refactor "supervisor" service restart in nailgun::supervisor,
  because default /etc/init.d/supervisord behavior during stop is
  not reliable enough and may end with "1" exit code if supervisor
  takes more than 60 seconds to stop its services.

Change-Id: I100c7705eb5515158bd940519fc02323c0bbe983
Related-bug: #1350764
'}, {'created': '2014-08-06 16:10:59.000000000', 'message': 'Refactor dockerctl attach and supervisor stop

- Create new file host-upgrade.pp that should be used for Fuel
  upgrades instead of host-only.pp. Upgrade mode excludes
  supervisor from upgrades. Fuel upgrade utility will install
  new supervisor configuration independent of Puppet.
- Refactor dockerctl attach function to provide possibility to
  correctly handle SIGINT sent from supervisord during stop
  process. In order to do so we fork "docker attach" and run loop
  in order to "trap" (catch) SIGINT/SIGTERM and shutdown container
  properly
- Use SIGTERM instead of SIGINT for dhcrelay_monitor supervisor
  service, because we have "sleep 30" loop in the monitor script,

commit_message:
Revamp supervisor docker, Create host upgrade w/o supervisor

- Create new file host-upgrade.pp that should be used for Fuel
  upgrades instead of host-only.pp. Upgrade mode excludes
  supervisor from upgrades. Fuel upgrade utility will install
  new supervisor configuration independent of Puppet.
- Refactor dockerctl attach function to provide possibility to
  correctly handle SIGINT sent from supervisord during stop
  process. In order to do so we fork "docker attach" and run loop
  in order to "trap" (catch) SIGINT/SIGTERM and shutdown container
  properly
- Use SIGTERM instead of SIGINT for dhcrelay_monitor supervisor
  service, because we have "sleep 30" loop in the monitor script,
  so it will handle SIGINT only when sleep ends.
- Break dependency of docker build on supervisor

Change-Id: I100c7705eb5515158bd940519fc02323c0bbe983
Related-bug: #1350764
Partial-bug: #1358144

Add database model to store snapshots

This adds a new table to store stack snapshots, and the APIs to access
it.

Co-Authored-By: ala.rezmerita@cloudwatt.com

I'm fine with this change, just want to understand how that works."}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2014-08-19 15:14:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Yuriy, there's no documented setup for this integration. I plan to document this once we switch to a new translation server.

For oslo.concurrency the two Jenkins jobs are:
1) https://jenkins.openstack.org/job/oslo.concurrency-propose-translation-update/ - which imports from transifex and proposes a patch
2) https://jenkins.openstack.org/job/oslo.concurrency-upstream-translation-update/ which takes strings from oslo.concurrency and pushes them to transifex.

The scripts call "python setup.cfg extract_messages" to extract messages and also "python update_catalog". extract_messages is used by 2), while update_catalog is part of 1). The Jenkins script then push the files to/from transifex.

If you want to see this in action for other projects, see https://review.openstack.org/#/q/branch:master+topic:transifex/translations,n,z

Hope that helps a bit.'}, {'account_id': 708, 'date': '2014-08-20 09:44:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
Initial translation setup

Add oslo.concurrency/locale/oslo.concurrency.pot, the file needs to
exist so that the infra scripts for sending translations work.

This file will then be updated via the proposol bot.

Change-Id: I7373cbd961b25a3a22e50c4f2ee9d32505cb3663

commit_message:
Shard expiring object container

All the expiring objects for a given X-Delete-At are funnelled into the
same expiring object container- this can act as a bottleneck.

Change-Id: I288a177a7ae3e213c727a2a81fa76d4ef9cf7eb3

commit_message:
Added new tests for vCenter and fixed old

1. vCenter HA
2. vCenter VMDK driver
3. Changed test set on vcenter_one_node_simple
4. In fuel_web_client.py added volumes_vmdk option
5. For function create_server_for_migration added timeout option

updated:
1.quantity of slaves from 1 to 3
2.and slave_01=controller, slave_02=cinder
3.deleted should_fail variable
4.added in settings : tenant , pass and user
5.updated description of vcenter_vmdk test
6.updated verifying of server's connectivity according with
  real res number instead of comparison with empty string
7. added should fail variable with name of test

Implements: blueprint vcenter-hv-full-scale-support
Change-Id: Id70258b405a6176a7e2bc198e3f541a60b2d4aae

commit_message:
Framework to start/stop neutron services for functional testing.

The purpose of this module is being able to start/stop server/agents
at will during tests, with specific configurations to ease testing
of several components together, or testing them throught it's API/RPC.

Change-Id: I6c5202927f6a1a5905ab5d6444a346f0ab0bbc38

commit_message:
Data processing templates tables refactoring

Remove 'data_processing.cluster_templates/_nodegroups_list.html'
and 'data_processing.nodegroup_templates/_processes_list.html'
templates and make corresponding lists at the Cluster Templates
and Node Group Templates tables using standard Column class
attributes.

Closes-Bug: #1356836

Change-Id: I82aa325ed27e06bd4652df7934488e67bd5e514b

commit_message:
internalURL should use the internalURL variable

This patches what appears to be a typo where the internalURL passed to
openstack_identity_register with the "adminURL" variable instead of the
internalURL variable that is defined earlier in the code.

This was noticed as the cookbook was setting up the endpoints with the
internalURL defined to the admin endpoint.  This is opposite to
OpenStack documentation and breaks operations of other openstack
projects which rely on internalURL.  For example the admin pipeline does
not have user_CRUD, while the public one does, breaking dashboard.

Following the inclusion of this patch the identity-internal endpoint
will need to be added to cookbook-chef-common.  Following that addition
the number of node.set for the identity-internal endpoint can be
reduced.

Partial-Bug: #1356732

Change-Id: I4bc3d49fd15b7254976a5ed8e964a4b3e3af02c6

commit_message:
Fix XSS issue with the unordered_list filter

When using the unordered_list filter in a Horizon table (as opposed to
a template directly), autoescaping is not set by default and the input
wasn't sanitised.

Closes-Bug: #1349491
Change-Id: Id82eefe48ccb17a158751ec65d24f3ac779380ec

commit_message:
Fix XSS issue with the unordered_list filter

When using the unordered_list filter in a Horizon table (as opposed to
a template directly), autoescaping is not set by default and the input
wasn't sanitised.

Closes-Bug: #1349491
Change-Id: Id82eefe48ccb17a158751ec65d24f3ac779380ec

commit_message:
Remove hardcoded version.

We use semantic versioning, not pbr's pre-version facility. This
line causes local package builds to have the wrong version, and
pbr will in future detect this and error.

Change-Id: I0d24872e1df219b89adddd9d53a6247b91e88ff0
