[{'created': '2014-08-20 11:04:07.000000000', 'message': "Adding GPFS Manila driver

Supporing GPFS exports over kernel NFS and Ganesha NFS
Supporting following Manila functionality:
1. Create, List, Delete Shares
2. Create, List, Delete Share Snapshots
3. Create Share from a Share Snapshot
4. Allow, Deny access to a share based on IP

Supports, local and remote GPFS nodes to the Manila service node,
in a GPFS cluster

Limitation:
1. While using remote GPFS node, with Ganesha NFS, 'gpfs_private_key'
for remote login to the GPFS node must be specified and there must be
a passwordless authentication already setup between the Manila and the
remote GPFS node.

Change-Id: I546e78f17cd3fdab2036439d871934e9499217fb
Implements: blueprint gpfs-driver
"}]
commit_message:
Adding GPFS Manila driver

Supporing GPFS exports over kernel NFS and Ganesha NFS
Supporting following Manila functionality:
1. Create, List, Delete Shares
2. Create, List, Delete Share Snapshots
3. Create Share from a Share Snapshot
4. Allow, Deny access to a share based on IP

Supports, local and remote GPFS nodes to the Manila service node,
in a GPFS cluster

Limitation:
1. While using remote GPFS node, with Ganesha NFS, 'gpfs_private_key'
for remote login to the GPFS node must be specified and there must be
a passwordless authentication already setup between the Manila and the
remote GPFS node.

Change-Id: I546e78f17cd3fdab2036439d871934e9499217fb
Implements: blueprint gpfs-driver

commit_message:
Avoid unneeded use of set, and use list instead

This doesn't change anything, except fixing an unneeded compatibility
issue with py2.6.

Change-Id: I4bb7f6bea9fd34fdec8af3eed702c5a8743d3178

commit_message:
test_hotplug_nic wait for the guest

The hot_plug nic test expect the new nic is visible,
on the guest almost immediately after the server
 associated to a port.

It is not  true, even the guest needs some time to initialize
the interface.

This change gives time:
* to the guest to realize the new interface.
* to nova/libvirt to actually finish the interface plugging.

Also having the call_until_true calls to respect the configured,
timeout settings and using an exception instead of an assert.

Change-Id: I018e6edefdd3a2f3b8c8d408291464cb28bc8e1e
Closes-Bug: #1358634

commit_message:
Volume Replication implementation for IBM Storwize/SVC

Adds replication support to the IBM Storwize/SVC driver.
Supports IBM SVC stretched Cluster mode.

DocImpact

Unit-Test will catch up later
Working-in-progress

Implements: blueprint volume-replication

Change-Id: I0008a6d061fdfc0794dbf2048e6c6e8c887fc6ee

commit_message:
Rename marconi to zaqar

Rename everywhere, sync template.rst with version in specs.

Adjust publishing URL, specs will show up on specs.openstack.org.

Create link to specs directory so that building works - like it's done
in other specs repositories.

Implements blueprint: project-rename
Change-Id: Ife866fafb9e1d94935bd0c02949e1cd9d5a9c281

Hi Armando:

Actually the FW and Router can be created in either order. If the router is created later - as such there is no issue - on a router create - the agent picks that up - 
https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/neutron/services/firewall/agents/l3reference/firewall_l3_agent.py#L229
and installs the FW on the new router and this should very well drive the FW to a final state rather than be stuck in PENDING_CREATE. So under normal conditions this is handled.

Now if a router never came around or if some how a router is created and before the agent installs the FW rules we have an issue on the router or if there is some other kind of race - we could land up getting stuck.

Perhaps forcing just a router sync could speed up the availability of routerinfo when the are created in close proximity - which  can help. But doing the services sync is a pretty heavy operation as it triggers a complete download from the plugin.'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-08-19 21:13:03.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-19 21:13:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-08-19 21:48:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hi Sridar,

I am still testing the waters right now. I am still unclear whether this is the right fix, but this is definitely the least intrusive (once I've proven it works ;)

Having said that, in order for a firewall to move from PENDING_CREATE to CREATE once the router is actually provisioned by the L3 agent we'd need an intra-agent mechanism to notify the fw-side of things that the router has actually been provisioned. Using services_sync is slightly more expensive as it goes all the way to server when it shouldn't. I'll see if I can optimize this once I got a better picture of what is going on.

Thanks,
Armando"}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2014-08-19 21:51:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Surely understand - i am not clear if something has changed with DVR, but in the old world - the method pointed to in my prev comment is kicked off from l3agent when it gets a router added msg - sort of a call out serving as the intra agent notification mechanism which is what triggers the FW Agent to install the rules and tell the plugin side of the world that it is done to drive the state.

commit_message:
Fix firewall state stuck in PENDING_CREATE

Kick off a services_sync check, in case no routers
have been found when firewalls are being set up.

This addresses the race condition when the firewall
side of the l3 agent and the router-side of the l3
agent are out of sync: the firewall is being created
but the router is not there yet.

In this case, without a full service sync the firewall
agent is unable to process the router, even though the
router is made available at a later moment. The flag
is then reset, after the periodic task if everything
goes back to normal.

Closes-bug: #1314313

Change-Id: Id8c0df4a5abb16dbdab0dc7e14c28f83d4e594af

commit_message:
Add sync_ceph_time method to all Ceph tests

Sometimes after reverting snapshots Ceph health check
alerts about clock skew on some nodes, so an additional
time sync and ceph service restart were added to the
test. Also, refactored methods which are used for ceph
checks.

Change-Id: I6c875f19cd3802e8280de48d121b7900b25a0f3a
Closes-bug: #1349379
(cherry picked from commit 3c7a8aa6e35d9e4ae36c8b2ae3ea39baec76a211)

commit_message:
Order execution of environment.d scripts

In case there are dependencies between scripts, IE one script defines an
env var another relies on. This change should be in line with current
expectations, given the convention is to numerically prefix scripts in
this directory.

This change updates dib-utils/bin/dib-run-parts to match the version in
DIB.

Relates-to: Ibfb562c5970b40598fc95da1e8d4beb9d51d7612
Change-Id: If3dd3924c3293ec33e82df82af533508c1e480ec

I have one more comment regarding the structure. The purpose of this blueprint is to simplify the adding of new snmp meters, right? Wouldn't it be nice to separate the "user-defined" or should I say "meter definition" code from the actual logic? For example, putting the MAPPING array and the _post_op functions in a new file. And having implementations of _post_op functions first, so you can put them directly in the mapping, not via a string.

At the moment it's very confusing. You have a map at the top, with _post_op keys defined as strings, then at the bottom you have those _post_op functions actually implemented, all the while they are called using getattr.

Just an idea, what do you think?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-25 07:34:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

@Nejc, We have discussed about putting the mapping in another file or even in another format during the spec review process. It looks like that requires the same amount of effort to add new meters, but add more effort to write the glue logic of importing new mappings from other files or of other forms. So we decide to use the current python dict format for mapping. 

For the post_op thing, this should be a special case, and should not be the common case for adding new meters. However, if you think this is not the rare case, I'm ok to move the post_op out of the SNMPInspector. Just want to hear others' opinion."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-28 18:26:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: -Verified

commit_message:
Added new hardware inspector interface

Added a new hardware inspector interface: inspect_generic and its snmp
implementation. The old interface will be removed later.

Partial implements: blueprint snmp-improvement.
Partial-Bug: 1286132

Change-Id: I847cfdad5b6571c4d066250617050a8f0b1cfbc4

commit_message:
System Test for Backup and restore of Fuel Master

Added tests backup feature:
-Accessibility of lrzip archive in /var/backup/fuel/
-Nailgun accessibility after backup
-For base(only master), simle, ha modes.

Added tests restore feature:
-md5sum of specific file before/afrer restore
-Nailgun accessibility after restore
-For base(only master), simle, ha modes.

blueprint system-tests-for-backup-and-restore

Change-Id: I7f9cb8765a89f270d223b516ac70bf87e5bfc53f

commit_message:
correct the syntax to select neutron database

the mysql command reads as "use database neutron;" which is not the
correct syntax. This patch changes it to "use neutron;"

Change-Id: I9b67cd40f43e7ee853edb2ab50789512bab009e9
Closes-Bug: #1359102

commit_message:
Fix primary in glossterm

Fix a previous change, the primary is the name that will be displayed in
the index. If networks is used, then entries like MTU will not show up
at all. Thus add them.

Change-Id: Ibadd762597d54992dc275bce7ae5a3ae3770a98c

commit_message:
Add firewall traffic on port 27410

The seed VM will attempt to send a Heat signal to a mocked Heat service
on the Jenkins slave where devtest_*.sh runs.

Open up port 27410 to accept that incoming traffic.

Required for: Ibfd20bf632cdf3381615dad68ecf620685553d5f
Alternative-to: I9e85f34339d7943a3a37a3b6772b9eb8ac85bf6c
Alternative-to: Idf1ca79ed653f2a62ee853b16f7c3fe14b7667cd

Change-Id: Ib52efa0f3f7c26d00fee7c14ffad6a812766dd0d

Set next version to 2014.2

pbr pre-versioning causes current sdist to have versions leading up to 0.4.1,
but that is already released - we should be leading up to 2014.2.

[{'created': '2014-05-27 14:04:07.000000000', 'message': 'ipmi double bridging functionality

ipmitool utility already supports double bridging.
Have made necessary changes to bring ipmitool double bridging
functionality to ironic.

Change-Id: I78e024a6205b0a87e50fbf0d93e69ef415be0934
'}, {'created': '2014-05-28 14:00:28.000000000', 'message': 'ipmi double bridging functionality

Enables ipmitool double bridging functionality in ironic

Change-Id: I78e024a6205b0a87e50fbf0d93e69ef415be0934
'}, {'created': '2014-06-05 07:27:03.000000000', 'message': 'ipmi double bridging functionality

Enables ipmitool double bridging functionality in ironic

In ipmitool there are two different bridging arguement specifications:
* single bridge (-t <target_address> [-b <target_channel>])
* double bridge (-T <transit_address> [-B <transit_channel>])
one can also specify the local IPMB address using -m <local_address>

When registering an baremetal node which requires double bridging, the
appropriate parameters can be specified to ipmi power driver as follows:
-i ipmi_local_address=<value>
-i ipmi_transit_channel=<value>
-i ipmi_transit_address=<value>
-i ipmi_target_channel=<value>
-i ipmi_target_address=<value>

Implements blueprint enabling-ipmi-double-bridge-support

Change-Id: I78e024a6205b0a87e50fbf0d93e69ef415be0934

commit_message:
IPMI double bridging functionality

Enables ipmitool bridging functionality in ironic

In ipmitool there are two different bridging argument specifications:
* single bridge (-t <target_address> [-b <target_channel>])
* double bridge (-T <transit_address> [-B <transit_channel>])
one can also specify the local IPMB address using -m <local_address>

When registering an baremetal node which requires bridging, the
appropriate parameters should be specified to ironic IPMI power
driver as follows:
-i ipmi_bridging=<single/dual/no>
-i ipmi_local_address=<value>
-i ipmi_transit_channel=<value>
-i ipmi_transit_address=<value>
-i ipmi_target_channel=<value>
-i ipmi_target_address=<value>

The parameter 'ipmi_bridging' should specify the type of bridging
required(single/dual) to access the baremetal node.
If the parameter is not specified, the default value will be set
to "no"

  Single Bridging:
    ironic node-create -d pxe_ipmitool [-i ipmi_local_address=VALUE]
    <-i ipmi_bridging=single> <-i ipmi_target_channel=VALUE>
    <-i ipmi_target_address=VALUE> ...

  Double Bridging:
    ironic node-create -d pxe_ipmitool [-i ipmi_local_address=VALUE]
    <-i ipmi_bridging=dual>  <-i ipmi_transit_channel=VALUE>
    <-i ipmi_transit_address=VALUE>  <-i ipmi_target_channel=VALUE>
    <-i ipmi_target_address=VALUE>  ...

The parameter 'ipmi_local_address' is optional. If the
parameter is not specified, it is auto discovered by ipmitool

Implements blueprint enabling-ipmi-double-bridge-support

Change-Id: I78e024a6205b0a87e50fbf0d93e69ef415be0934

Stack-delete was failing periodically because of heat bug
https://bugs.launchpad.net/heat/+bug/1299259, whereby there's
an implicit dependency from floating IPs to the router interface.
There is a fix in progress for heat, but until then, this patch
adds an explicit depends_on to the router interface.

commit_message:
Fix occasional deletion failure

Stack-delete was failing periodically because of heat bug
https://bugs.launchpad.net/heat/+bug/1299259, whereby there's
an implicit dependency from floating IPs to the router interface.
There is a fix in progress for heat, but until then, this patch
adds an explicit depends_on to the router interface.

Change-Id: I846abf1fbd90d5f5c71b1c13941463743ace48ad
Closes-Bug: 1356721

commit_message:
Remove hardcoded version

Generally everything other than API servers uses semantic versioning,
not pbr's pre-version facility. This line causes local package builds
to have the wrong version today (0.3.dev when 2014.2 is the version
under development), and pbr will in future detect this and error. If
Murano wants to use preversioning for the agent, this can instead be
changed to

  version = 2014.2

Change-Id: If65a92f8673faefd77419354f24ba38c0c18c05f

commit_message:
fuel_upgrade: add KillSupervisord hook

We should kill supervisor daemon in case we're going to upgrade master
node from 5.0, because of broken supervisor configs.

Change-Id: I77ecbf0fb2df2ab8b5441dc9996149add3e0a52d
Related-Bug: #1350764

commit_message:
verify vCenter input fields on Settings tab

- this change allows us to validate vCenter related fields on Settings
  tab; it will not allow user to start deployment with empty values
- username field must be not empty
- password field must be not empty
- vCenter IP must be valid IPv4 address
- while here rename 'ip_regex' to 'ipv4_regex', to reflect the fact
  that this regular expression does not validate IPv6 addresses
- while here rename 'non_empty_regex' to 'non_empty_string', actually
  first name is missleading, regular expression match non empty strings,
  it does not means that RE itself is empty
- while here adjust message in wizard about "vCenter IP" field, lets
  explicitly state that we expect IPv4 address as input value

Change-Id: I60b0cbdf9a3801ba94483b1224f79786b37ce921
Closes-bug: #1314613

commit_message:
make use of $SYSTEMD_SYSTEM_UNIT_DIR

Use $SYSTEMD_SYSTEM_UNIT_DIR (I413a92284e6a79e7fcdde99c5138bc3ce8e85e80)
instead of the hardcoded path to the systemd service directory.

Change-Id: Ifed56382d0507c04b61462211134d52c2cc220e5

commit_message:
Supports DEFAULT group opts in TempestPrivateConfig

Options from the DEFAULT group are not accessible via the config
proxy. Adding support for DEFAULT group opts in TempestPrivateConfig to
solve that.

Partially implements bp:test-accounts

Change-Id: Ia80c703080870427bbacc12a239e385d9927631f

http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 7249, 'date': '2014-07-28 10:38:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2014-07-28 11:21:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I think the approach is good, but instead of having a whole module for icehouse models, could there be a way to just build them as a diff with frozen models?

Just a few models changed from icehouse to healing.
for all others, having a whole not module seems just a rather pointless repetition.

I think we could have a icehouse_frozen_models module which is pretty much the one you're doing here, and then a healing_frozen_models module where we import icehouse frozen models and redefine those which have changed.

Another way would be using setattr to alter models which change but this will probably harm readability.

Summarizing, I think this is ok and the only further bit we need to agree on is how to reduce code duplication on model definition."}, {'account_id': 7249, 'date': '2014-07-28 11:26:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Salvatore Orlando

Yes, of course here is to much duplication there.  This is just the first testing patch set to see what needs to be done. The situation of this patch has been discussed with Mark McClain.

It was concluded that we should go for the easiest approach rather than have another freeze point. 

the following considerations were made:
1) havana is going to be unsupported for Kilo release
 2) most people will upgrade from icehouse, while a minor percentage from havana
 3) downgrade use cases are mostly to revert after failed upgrades

Therefore, unless we are missing some use case, for this release we will support upgrade from havana, but not downgrade to havana. In this case we will need to: a) raise on dowgrade at icehouse migration b) remove all downgrade code for migrations from havana to icehouse, and we could do that while making them unconditional".

therefore unless we have use cases for supporting downgrade I would back this solution. So far I see no obvious use case beyond the fact that alembic allows for that. But if we raise in a migration we'll put a block on alembic so that should be fine imho.'}, {'account_id': 7249, 'date': '2014-08-20 11:55:01.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
labs: add init_node command

This changeset adds a new init_node command for config/scripts.* and
uses it to merge scripts.nodeinit_osbash and scripts.nodeinit_vagrant
into the node specific config/scripts.*.

This results in some redundancy, but it (hopefully) makes the script
configuration easier to follow. It also makes the initial creation and
configuration of the VM just another step that can be picked or omitted
from script configuration.

Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs
Change-Id: Ieadfe2b9540710556100051723e3e6f08855efa3

commit_message:
Bump osprofiler requirement to 0.3.0

ofprofiler.notifier.create, which is used by recently merged
commit 94b670c199fcc39784edd90b323b0396914ce66a, does not seem
available in osprofiler 0.1.1.

Closes-Bug: #1354500
Change-Id: I563558efcf4e909e2a97003bf84a0785091fd360

commit_message:
Improved error handling for provisioning operations

1. Removed all error handling in provisioning engine and moved it
   to ops.
2. Implemented general logic on handling with deleted cluster

Implements blueprint error-handling-in-provisioning

Change-Id: Ia161dea1c726bd95157a279eb0f2917af2516b07

commit_message:
Update tox.ini pep8 config to ignore i18n functions

Oslo i18n introduced separate translation functions for logging.
This patch modifies tox.ini to ignore those additional functions
as well, not just _().

Change-Id: I9d201a8cdc5113d1c60aed17bf593dda212e5d2a

commit_message:
Bump oslotest version

Latest oslotest releases automatically stop mock patches in tearDown().
This allows project that are using the library to get rid of lots of
redundant patch.stop() calls.

Bumping the version of the module to facilitate usage of the feature in
unit tests.

Related-Bug: 1323214
Change-Id: I58e32630b1b43a027a775cbf2a338bf928b4a71b

[{'created': '2014-08-20 11:27:36.000000000', 'message': "Adding GPFS Manila driver

Supporing GPFS exports over kernel NFS and Ganesha NFS
Supporting following Manila functionality:
1. Create, List, Delete Shares
2. Create, List, Delete Share Snapshots
3. Create Share from a Share Snapshot
4. Allow, Deny access to a share based on IP

Supports, local and remote GPFS nodes to the Manila service node,
in a GPFS cluster

Limitation:
1. While using remote GPFS node, with Ganesha NFS, 'gpfs_private_key'
for remote login to the GPFS node must be specified and there must be
a passwordless authentication already setup between the Manila and the
remote GPFS node.

Change-Id: I7a02a6ed79e62b5a4983800923597433fac3df46
Implements: blueprint gpfs-driver
"}]
commit_message:
Adding GPFS Manila driver

Supporing GPFS exports over kernel NFS and Ganesha NFS
Supporting following Manila functionality:
1. Create, List, Delete Shares
2. Create, List, Delete Share Snapshots
3. Create Share from a Share Snapshot
4. Allow, Deny access to a share based on IP

Supports, local and remote GPFS nodes to the Manila service node,
in a GPFS cluster

Limitation:
1. While using remote GPFS node, with Ganesha NFS, 'gpfs_private_key'
for remote login to the GPFS node must be specified and there must be
a passwordless authentication already setup between the Manila and the
remote GPFS node.

Change-Id: I7a02a6ed79e62b5a4983800923597433fac3df46
Implements: blueprint gpfs-driver

- Check environment list
- Check package list
- Check category list

commit_message:
Increase source-repositories support for tarballs

The existing support for tar files in source-repositories saves
only the contents within subdirectories contained in the archive.

This change makes the selection of contents within the tarball user-
definable based on the REPOREF specified (or overridden in the env).

A REPOREF of '*' (the current default, but deprecated) will select
the contents of subdirectories within the archive, while '.' will
select the entire contents of the archive.

For reference:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-August/043197.html
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-August/043249.html

Change-Id: I45db42ce66bf1d63d6ab5730090bf458b1b37ce9

commit_message:
Add all neutron packages to requirements

It has come up in several requests that we should have packages present for
 all of the neutron components so that any patches we might have included are
 present in the repos on the fuel-master.

This is not intended to be a "fuel suppports ..." but rather enables users to
 customize their deployment accordingly and not have to find packages that
 where not built from the same sources which would cause more problems for
 them.

Change-Id: I25299df0cb331186187e47920c01231181051f7f
Closes-bug: #1330610
Related-blueprint: ml2-neutron

commit_message:
Set python hash seed to 0 in tox.ini

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but glance unittests don't currently pass
with a random hash seed so set it to the python default seed.

This change will allow us to use new tox again and remove the
restriction on tox<=1.6.1 to run unittests.

Redundant setenvs for specific test envs are removed to prevent them
from overriding the PYTHONHASHSEED value.

Note this change will need to be backported to the stable branches to
keep unittests there working with new tox as well.

Change-Id: Id0175b7a95c0ad07798b4603b5d1dd8e6d414561
(cherry picked from commit 90c07019350adc301fa5d91239ebfb16fcac775f)

commit_message:
Add in text for text mode on trusty

This should be fine for other distros and Ubuntu versions since
the kernel command line is a well known loosely-coupled interface.

Trusty changed the way to get text mode consoles (again) and since
we're deploying servers, where graphics is an anti-feature, lets
work around it by default, again.

Also update test_pxe.test__build_pxe_config to work with the new
kernel option.

updates Ipxe and IPA deploy templates too.

Change-Id: Id42bd362477b1e8dbbd5f2a6188cebacc8a0323a

commit_message:
Fix failing of unittests in one thread

With change of default driver, that is used for unittests one additional
method 'ensure_share' was not mocked, that caused problems running
unittests in one thread.

Change-Id: Iea08207bb6200c37f5608d222dccdfbdc509b234
Closes-Bug: #1358854

Make Vagrant skip not only osbash commands (lines starting with "cmd "),
but also scripts in the osbash directory. This allows us to use the same
config/scripts.* files for osbash and Vagrant while preventing Vagrant

Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs

commit_message:
labs: skip osbash scripts in Vagrant

Make Vagrant skip not only osbash commands (lines starting with "cmd "),
but also scripts in the osbash directory. This allows us to use the same
config/scripts.* files for osbash and Vagrant while preventing Vagrant
from executing scripts that are only meant for osbash.

Change-Id: I86d1bb6065a58edcc67015603da59af9d6aff4c7
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs

commit_message:
labs: split out vm_init_node

Move the initial creation and configuration of a node into a separate
function. Follow-up patches give the option to omit a call to this
function, which allows osbash to continue work on a node rather than
having to recreate it for each run.

Change-Id: Id58a5f572de0b6453cf24533b2b4e2337f35803f
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs

commit_message:
Enforce image_size_cap on v2 upload

image_size_cap should be checked and enforced on upload

Enforcement is in two places:
- on image metadata save
- during image save to backend store

(cherry picked from commit 92ab00fca6926eaf3f7f92a955a5e07140063718)
Conflicts:
	glance/location.py
	glance/tests/functional/v2/test_images.py
	glance/tests/unit/test_store_image.py

Closes-Bug: 1315321
Change-Id: I45bfb360703617bc394e9e27fe17adf43b09c0e1
Co-Author: Manuel Desbonnet <manuel.desbonnet@hp.com>

commit_message:
Correct InstanceNotifier yaml stub

Addition to reviews/113676 (reducing number of api requests during
deploy). InstanceNotifier yaml stub was mistakenly called
InstanceReportNotifier; patch corrects manifest.yaml and the class
name, and renames the yaml file.

Change-Id: I47c143ed92456374936e13bb27ae5988e5676e8e
Closes-Bug: 1358061

commit_message:
Convert rescue v3 plugin to v2.1 API

Changes required to have v3 plugin natively support the V2.1
API.

The parameters admin_password and image_ref were reverted to
adminPass and rescue_image_ref

Partially implements v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I98af0b4ce1a37ed0cdede6802cbdb96d0e372619

commit_message:
Enables no auth for public endpoints

Any endpoint that does not depend on tenant/user should be
accessible without any auth.
Remove confusing/unnecessary 'v1/public' endpoint. we already have
public endpoints that does not have 'v1/public' prefix and we don't
have to force URI to use this prefix to make it public.
User should also be able to list solum supported language packs without
any auth (this will be addressed in a separate commit).

Closes-Bug: #1357539, #1348759
Change-Id: I62bfe7afaf2815455c7d868a3af82b0ffba81709

commit_message:
Next version is 2014.2.1.

pbr pre-versioning causes current sdist to have versions leading up to
2014.1.0, but that is a release in the past...  already released - we
should be leading up to 2014.2, but solum already has a tag of
2014.2.0 (which is equivalent to 2014.2) so we need to increment the
minor version getting 2014.2.1.

Change-Id: Id2a89ec88a8b8b721abddd5f42d2e53069ebd8b5

commit_message:
router service plugin: Simplify hosting device driver

As server.create method of nova client accepts files argument as
dict. Its dict value can be either file-like object or string object.
By passing string object instead of file object, the logic can be
simplified.

Change-Id: I763aaa288c5f38dd34b85954cd05d83d4bcd3604

commit_message:
Fix misspelled class name AmbigiousAuthSystem

Class name AmbigiousAuthSystem in exc.py is misspelled.
To fix the issue, this patch renames AmbigiousAuthSystem to
AmbiguousAuthSystem in exc.py and creates an alias for compatibility.
Also edits the use of the class in client.py accordingly and adds an
additional assertRaises() to
test_client.py.test_get_client_no_url_and_no_token to test both the
correct exception and the alias.

Change-Id: I18309b045d5eb9e81c72b1ed9de350925927db66
Closes-Bug: 1356512

commit_message:
Enforce image_size_cap on v2 upload

image_size_cap should be checked and enforced on upload

Enforcement is in two places:
- on image metadata save
- during image save to backend store

(cherry picked from commit 92ab00fca6926eaf3f7f92a955a5e07140063718)
Conflicts:
	glance/location.py
	glance/tests/functional/v2/test_images.py

Closes-Bug: 1315321
Change-Id: I45bfb360703617bc394e9e27fe17adf43b09c0e1
Co-Author: Manuel Desbonnet <manuel.desbonnet@hp.com>

[{'account_id': 7186, 'date': '2014-05-05 09:55:14.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 7186, 'date': '2014-05-05 09:59:47.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 7186, 'date': '2014-05-05 10:20:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1

Putting this as WIP
Instructions on how to experiment with it: https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/external-auth-federation-mapping'}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2014-05-05 11:13:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

If support for Apache federated authn has been implemented correctly in Keystone then it should be trivial to swap federation protocol modules in Apache without effecting Keystone at all (apart from changing the details of the IDP). If Keystone has to be changed because Apache is using OpenID instead of SAML, then there is something fundamentally wrong with the Keystone design. I have added a note to the Etherpad to ask why saml2 is present in Keystone if OpenID is being used in Apache'}, {'account_id': 7186, 'date': '2014-05-05 11:49:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: -Workflow

This is an early PoC with the bare minimum to demo what's described in the bp. At this current stage the saml2 method is needed since the federation auth endpoint hardcodes it in the payload regardless of the real method used, see https://github.com/openstack/keystone/blob/master/keystone/contrib/federation/controllers.py#L233

I intend to condition this value to the presence of the REMOTE_USER env variable."}, {'account_id': 7186, 'date': '2014-05-05 11:50:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 8978, 'date': '2014-05-30 10:07:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I think current logic is not very usable, but we are on a good way.

Looking at the blueprint, your basic rule will map every user from the trusted IdP, and assign him hardcoded group. This mean every user from CERN's 40k users ldap database will be able to get a token with this group. More realistic use-case would be 'Assign this group to every IT dep employee', but this would require Keystone to take IdP attributes into consideration."}, {'account_id': 5046, 'date': '2014-05-30 12:54:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)'}, {'account_id': 7186, 'date': '2014-06-12 20:48:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-12 20:48:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

This requested change should be covered by the re-engineering we are currently performing to keystone federation, as discussed in Atlanta and shown in the ppt here

http://www.slideshare.net/davidwchadwick/keystone-apach-authn

I suggest that your change can be abandoned or at least temporarily suspended until the re-engineering has been finalised. You can resurrect it then if you don't think your concerns have adequately been addressed."}, {'account_id': 7186, 'date': '2014-06-13 08:21:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Steve Martinelli:
I have started working on this after observing two things: first, keystone is easily extendable with apache auth mods and the external auth plugin, but the downside is that the authenticating users have to be in keystone's users backend; secondly, I couldn't use the keystone federation and mapping support with other apache mods than mod_shib, because they would set the REMOTE_USER env variable and that would trigger an interception by the external auth plugin in keystone before mapping operations can be done. As it is, it is impossible to define a mapping in keystone using REMOTE_USER as a remote element.

This PoC is therefore simply an attempt to combine the flexibility of the external auth plugin with the mapping functionalities brought by federation in keystone. This would potentially allow using any apache auth mod to authenticate against an external IdP of the supported protocol, without the need to provision the users in keystone, just like with saml2. A use case could be: a public cloud provider wants to offer a test access to limited resources without registration, and use a common authentication system such as openID.

@David Chadwick: Indeed, this looks very close, is there an ongoing review for this effort ? I'd be happy to help."}, {'account_id': 8978, 'date': '2014-06-13 08:43:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I think Matthieu and Florent are trying to enrich 'external' mechanism with creating ephemeral users basing reusing the mapping engine. It has probably nothing in common with federation."}, {'account_id': 8978, 'date': '2014-06-13 12:09:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Some tests could be nice if you feel you want to carry on wihth your patch.'}, {'account_id': 6482, 'date': '2014-06-13 18:34:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Add MySQL-python and psycopg2 to test-requirements

If we suppose to run tests with real backends (test migrations), for
example, we suppose to have any connectors to these databases. Added
psycopg2 for connection to PostgreSQL and MySQL-python for MySQL.

Change-Id: I34c7bdd76781cbea0e2e758fe28276e1716c48aa

commit_message:
Fix XSS issue with the unordered_list filter

When using the unordered_list filter in a Horizon table (as opposed to
a template directly), autoescaping is not set by default and the input
wasn't sanitised.

Closes-Bug: #1349491
Change-Id: Id82eefe48ccb17a158751ec65d24f3ac779380ec

commit_message:
Automatically reset force_raw_images to be True

While using ceph rbd as imagebackend, it would be automatically reset
force_raw_images to be True.

Doc change reason:
When using a qcow2 to create a vm with rbd imagebackend, the vm can be
successfully created. Although vm's state is active, vm's console show
that it can not find boot disk. From ceph's docs, we find that Ceph only
works with raw volumes, so we need to convert an non-raw format image to
raw image when creating vm using rbd imagebackend.

Change-Id: I0518e04881ea309436a543af913e41f7abc91f05
Related-Bug: #1321141

commit_message:
Use wizard to make package uploading clear

This patch divides package uploading in two steps:
file uploading and package parameters modification.

If the package is application category should be provided

Modify Package form also was updated to support that behavior

Implements blueprint divide-upload-package-into-two-steps
Change-Id: Ic4d7834db7bb6e431ab90dbb733d85d966384f4d

commit_message:
Allow strings in heat SW config configSection

For non-structured configs, configSection cannot be restricted to a
Map. Patch removes the contract type, although it is worth revisiting
this to refactor slightly in future (which should be possible without
changing the interface).

Change-Id: I179e350a724965c97e90c3a1927f955c20cc2a72
Closes-Bug: 1358046

commit_message:
Add caller information to Begin execute log entry

This patch adds a new caller information logged by executor when a new MuranoPL
function is started. This will help to reconstruct a calls flow for debugging. Also it can
be used to create a graphical execution trace.

Change-Id: If53634994b99b9bdf68dd1a020f61abbbf656d4e

@xing-yang
You are right, currently this information is not used by driver. 
The idea of this patch is to make server-details mechanism so that driver can return server details after server creation and manager saves that data in DB. 
On operations like create_share/delete_share/allow_access etc. manager will retrieve server details from DB and pass it to driver.

commit_message:
labs: fix wbatch autostart_reset

The seemingly plausible construct used to chain two conditional commands
together doesn't work. The second command in the chain is executed
unconditionally.

The construct is replaced by a solution that lacks elegance but makes up
for it by working as intended.

Change-Id: I0bc60fdc061a51205cbbf101f6c5b16f85342afa
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs

This changeset introduces a new syntax for commands in the
config/scripts.* files.

Command lines start with "cmd " followed by a command (such as boot or
snapshot) and its arguments (if any).

This allows us to easily recognize command lines anywhere without having
to keep a complete command list.

Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs
Change-Id: I7a52476f5b9ba24c2746667b5a0b23b4b73d2e87
'}]
commit_message:
labs: new cmd syntax for config/scripts.*

This changeset introduces a new syntax for commands in the
config/scripts.* files.

Command lines start with "cmd " followed by a command (such as boot or
snapshot) and its arguments (if any).

This allows us to easily recognize command lines anywhere without having
to keep a complete command list.

Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs
Change-Id: I7a52476f5b9ba24c2746667b5a0b23b4b73d2e87

commit_message:
Catch exception.InUseByStore at API layer

If user create an image with Ceph backend driver, and then create
an instance based on the image. As a result, user will run into
500 error when deleting the image. Because rbd driver is raising
exception.InUseByStore()at [1] when the image is in use, but no
code to catch the exception at REST API layer.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/glance/blob/master/glance/store/rbd.py#L290

Closes-Bug: 1345942

Change-Id: I350c235944aab226dc96de169be2087e2b599ab4

Well done, Pablo :) Thank you for your patience!'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-03-13 20:42:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

This looks good and is not a bad approach. However, I think that with the new internal-callback structures it would make sense to have the managers listen for the events and handle the deletion that way rather than doing cross-manager calls.

if you take a look at 

http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/keystone/tree/keystone/common/dependency.py#n84

you can see that you can register a callback for specific events and take actions when those events occur. The basic premise is that in your ``__init__`` method you would define a property called ``event_callbacks`` dictionary that has the following structure (in the case of deletion):

    {
        'deleted': {
            '<resource_type, e.g. "user">': [
                callback_method1,
                ...
            ]
        }
    }

The callback methods would automatically get called by the notification infrastructure with a variety of information being passed to it that can be used to perform the desired actions.  See

http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/keystone/tree/keystone/notifications.py#n145

for the method that sends the event to the callback.

The advantage to this method is to help ensure that one manager doesn't need to know another manager's method signatures to signal some event happens. It also prevents the need to add an ever expanding list to (for example) identity.core of "handle_delete_<whatever>" methods that occur when a user is deleted.

The revoke api keystone.contrib.revoke implements this for issuing token revocation events (though it registers it's callbacks differently).'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-03-13 20:43:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Feel free to hit me up in IRC if you have any questions about my previous comment.'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2014-03-13 20:45:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I guess I prefer explicit calls to implicit callbacks.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-03-13 21:39:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
Use callback/notification framework for deletes

Renamed delete_user (now delete_user_notification_callback) and
delete_group (now delete_group_notification_callback) methods on
the assignment drivers. Updated to hook new callback functions
into the internal callback/notification framework so proper
cleanup actions can be taken on user/group deletion without
needing to make explicit cross-manager method calls.

Renamed credential_api methods and created a wrapper method
in token_api to match.

Co-Authored-By: Pablo Fernando Cargnelutti <pablo.fernando.cargnelutti@intel.com>
Change-Id: I4664e807ea7d712eecd942d7ef4d4a783f7ef0fe
Closes-Bug: #1222675

commit_message:
Remove resource_id_set(None) calls

This removes resetting resource_id in delete, as the state is storing
that information properly, and it doesn't provide any additional value.

Change-Id: I71f17ab79adbad5286389c87f1fbd5c60c4a8d7f
Closes-Bug: #1358492

commit_message:
Further pep8 fixes

Fix the following issues in some files:
F401 'XXX' imported but unused
E123 closing bracket does not match indentation of opening bracket's
line
E126 continuation line over-indented for hanging indent
E128 continuation line under-indented for visual indent
E129 visually indented line with same indent as next logical line
H904  Wrap long lines in parentheses instead of a backslash

Partial-Bug: #1333290
Change-Id: Ic9b3a1e47fd24d2835f35f2ef71c4519908ff049

commit_message:
Revert "Setup MySQL root password"

This is currently breaking my local devtest (and probably
CI once we try running with it).  MysqlRootPassword is
defined in the Heat template as a Resource, and passing it
in as a parameter causes the error:

ERROR: The Parameter (MysqlRootPassword) was not defined in
template.

Closes-Bug: 1358914

This reverts commit 8b049e4ed31c5c7797bf7b867a0d8c90cee40a79.

Change-Id: Ie17decadef997e3ee0b19f951347797c13e02c65

[{'created': '2014-08-01 16:04:37.000000000', 'message': "[WIP] BGP Dynamic Routing

BGP dynamic routing functionality. A new API extension to allow create
RoutingPeers (remote peers to which exchange routes) and
RoutingInstances, which can be seen as interchange policies: whether to
advertise, if so: which networks to advertise, and whether to discover.

Agent scheduling functionality has been added as well: by default, a
routing peer is scheduled to first available agent who asks for routes,
more or less like the L3 agent works.

A user is able to reschedule peers and instances to another agents and
disable auto-scheduling to gain more control or offer agent HA
functionality, for instance.

(Not developed yet). Agents are associated automatically to routing
instances too. The task that RoutingPeers do (what to advertise and
whether to discover), depend on the policies defined in the Routing
Instances. So agents can be seens as the relation between the two
entities.

The agent runs a periodic task that requests for a routes to advertise
. According to networks associated to routing instance, the
Dynamic Routing Plugin returns all the subnets created in the associated
networks.

(Not developed yet) At the same time, agent returns back the discovered
routes and Dynamic Routing Plugin is responsible to save it into
'extraroutes' table of the network's routers.

Change-Id: If55b5940c16c6fdd55cc15567b430b027b59a50b
"}, {'created': '2014-08-14 12:01:43.000000000', 'message': 'BGP Dynamic Routing: introduce routing peers

Neutron.

the upstream peers to exchange routes.

A new extension is added to add basic CRUD methods for routing peer entity,
as well as the migration script and the new service definition.

In this patch, routing peer does not interact with any of other entities of
Neutron.

commit_message:
BGP Dynamic Routing: introduce routing peers

This is the first patch to provide BGP dynamic routing functionality in
Neutron.

Basic new entity for BGP is the Routing Peer, to define from Neutron API
the upstream peers to exchange routes.

A new extension is added with basic CRUD methods to expose the routing
peer entity, as well as the migration script and the new service definition.

In this patch, routing peer does not interact with any of other entities of
Neutron.

Partial-Implements: blueprint bgp-dynamic-routing
Change-Id: If55b5940c16c6fdd55cc15567b430b027b59a50b

commit_message:
Add configuration variable for changing keymap

One would like to change their keymap setting of noVNC to match its keyboard.
This patch adds a new parameter "NOVA_VNC_KEYMAP" in order for setting keymap.
If this parameter is added to localrc, devstack adds the line,
"vnc_keymap = $NOVA_VNC_KEYMAP", to nova.conf.

For example, when one would like to use Japanese keymap, set NOVA_VNC_KEYMAP
in localrc as follows:

NOVA_VNC_KEYMAP=ja

Change-Id: Ifc80f9de95304aa9c047d08f0da05a46b79b423d
Implements: blueprint nova-vnc-keymap-support
Signed-off-by: Satoru Moriya <satoru.moriya.br@hitachi.com>

commit_message:
Allow rebuild of node in ERROR and DEPLOYFAIL state

This patch allows nodes in ERROR or DEPLOYFAIL state to be rebuilt. This
allows operators have a chance of recovering a node should it go into
an error state while deploying or rebuilding.

Change-Id: Ia7d6b3b796357da83fdb4d40f92f18a502956aa2
Closes-Bug: #1354437

commit_message:
Issue multiple SQL statements in separate engine.execute() calls

Some sqlalchemy drivers (eg: mysqlconnector) don't support
engine.execute("sql stmt 1; sql stmt 2;") and require a separate
execute() call for each SQL statement.  After discussions with
sqlalchemy author, he confirmed it would be better to fix callers rather
than attempt to patch in support for multiple statements.

With this patch, nova-manage db sync succeeds using mysqlconnector.

Change-Id: I57e6ecdafe90110eaffe757f0ef0bf7b41b0f3e3

commit_message:
Allow listing of resources from deleted stacks

This change complements the `show_deleted` flag added to stack-list and
allows for resources in a deleted stack to be listed as well.

Implements: blueprint stack-list-soft-deleted
Change-Id: I20ac5cb1039d12e4df30a01491f6ce15b5154f5b

commit_message:
Log task ID when the task status changes

This patch adds the task ID to the existing log messages which
occur when the task status changes, whether successful or a
failure.

Change-Id: Ie1ebdd92805370b706d8d9eec29d1b433095369a
Closes-Bug: 1358888

commit_message:
Add a tox job for generating docs

Add a tox job to make it easier for developers to generate their
own docs before submitting a patch.

Change-Id: I1897407d0db901c61360a196b365b0661eb65b66

commit_message:
Enable osprofiler interface in glanceclient shell

To help end user uses profiling by glanceclient CLI directly, the
change added '--profile <HMAC_KEY>' argument to the shell.

This change also fixed a function regression, it was used to pass
necessary trace info to glance server via http header:
https://github.com/openstack/python-glanceclient/commit/dbb242b776908ca50ed8557ebfe7cfcd879366c8#diff-740dd7d9149f46fe4c01ef0ab7eb3bfbL196

In addition:
1. If client app want to enable profiling feature for glanceclient
object, please see: http://paste.openstack.org/show/85722/
2. Afer adding more trace point into Client object, as fundamental
requirement of osprofiler, what we need to notice caller is providing
correct messaging notifier in the context code.

The relevant change for glance server is ready at:
I45a19f5eb5304c2b78a9e12cbc0744941a807304

DocImpact

Change-Id: If42b69b2695a5f88536ecbc2c1b3592d9dbd880a
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <lzy.dev@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Ensure server's SSL cert is validated

A bug was introduced which meant that the server SSL certificate was
not being verified. Here we make sure that it is checked (unless
the --insecure flag is used).

Helps guard against man-in-the-middle attack.

Change-Id: I08f30bf3906b6580c871729311343fa8eefda91b
Closes-bug: #1357430

commit_message:
Set python hash seed to 0 in tox.ini

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but ceilometer unittests don't currently
pass with a random hash seed so set it to the python default seed.

This change will allow us to use new tox again and remove the
restriction on tox<=1.6.1 to run unittests.

Redundant setenvs for specific test envs are removed to prevent them
from overriding the PYTHONHASHSEED value.

Note this change will need to be backported to the stable branches to
keep unittests there working with new tox as well.

Conflicts:
	tox.ini

Change-Id: Ibc613d77ad52d5f7d8d613f3dd66ffba4117ff72
(cherry picked from commit 860a2852ca92df20fa886cec2e75d753ac6e18bb)

commit_message:
Set python hash seed to 0 in tox.ini

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but glance unittests don't currently pass
with a random hash seed so set it to the python default seed.

This change will allow us to use new tox again and remove the
restriction on tox<=1.6.1 to run unittests.

Redundant setenvs for specific test envs are removed to prevent them
from overriding the PYTHONHASHSEED value.

Note this change will need to be backported to the stable branches to
keep unittests there working with new tox as well.

Conflicts:
	tox.ini

Change-Id: Id0175b7a95c0ad07798b4603b5d1dd8e6d414561
(cherry picked from commit 90c07019350adc301fa5d91239ebfb16fcac775f)

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-24 22:14:21.000000000', 'message': 'Implement a dialect-level function dispatch system

A new utility feature dispatch_for_dialect() is added, which
is intended to provide a single solution for the issue of many
areas within oslo.db where conditional per-database and/or
per-driver behavior is needed, such as that of setting up
special event listeners, connection options, or invoking
special features.  The dispatch_for_dialect() function is
essentially a decorator, which when invoked provides subsequent
"builder" decorators in the style of the Python @property
object and others, so that any number of functions can be
registered against database/driver matcher strings.  The system
supports "single" or "multiple" function call modes, wildcards
for both database and driver independently of each other,
support for URL strings, URL objects, Engine and Connection
objects as lead targets, and additional arguments and
return values for single mode.

The agenda of this feature is to provide the basis for the
removal of all remaining "if db.name == 'MYDB'" conditionals
throughout oslo.db and elsewhere.

Change-Id: I75201487c1481ffc83329a2eaaaa07acf5aac76e

commit_message:
Implement a dialect-level function dispatch system

A new utility feature dispatch_for_dialect() is added, which
is intended to provide a single solution for the issue of many
areas within oslo.db where conditional per-database and/or
per-driver behavior is needed, such as that of setting up
special event listeners, connection options, or invoking
special features.  The dispatch_for_dialect() function is
essentially a decorator, which when invoked provides subsequent
"builder" decorators in the style of the Python @property
object and others, so that any number of functions can be
registered against database/driver matcher strings.  The system
supports "single" or "multiple" function call modes, wildcards
for both database and driver independently of each other,
support for URL strings, URL objects, Engine and Connection
objects as lead targets, and additional arguments and
return values for single mode.

The agenda of this feature is to provide the basis for the
removal of all remaining "if db.name == 'MYDB'" conditionals
throughout oslo.db and elsewhere.

Change-Id: I75201487c1481ffc83329a2eaaaa07acf5aac76e

commit_message:
Provide a quick way to run flake8

"run_tests.sh -p" always checks every file for errors even though you
have probably only changed a handful. This patch adds "run_tests.sh -8"
which only checks the files that were modified in the HEAD commit or
the current working tree.

Copied from Matthew's work in Nova here:
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/110746/15

Change-Id: I84f6a522da5352a703caa59975643043ec1911fe
Co-Authored-By: Matthew Gilliard <matthew.gilliard@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Add new db api get functions for ec2_snapshot

This patch adds two new getters for EC2 snapshot mappings to the db
API.  The existing getters don't return the full db model.  Instead,
they only return an ID or UUID.  The full db model is needed when this
gets converted over to a nova object.

Related to blueprint convert-ec2-api-to-use-nova-objects

Change-Id: I8e2ed5086a7768f373d35c2f34386f2d30d11e07

commit_message:
enable multiple collector workers

currently, a single worker thread writes received samples into
database. this is fine for most occasions but during message
spikes, it is not enough. this patch increase amount of workers to
half the number of processors (so we can ensure ceilometer maintains
lightweight design)

this will also help validate mulitple worker setup works.

Partial-Bug: #1336755
Change-Id: I33037f2f9ebfda43238e5cd0cff75adbed65d055

[{'created': '2014-08-16 18:04:39.000000000', 'message': 'Fix sporadic false failure in xprofile unit test code

This is currently "experimental"... appears that what may have
been happening on feature/ec lately with a middleware failure

commit_message:
Fix sporadic false failure in xprofile unit test code

Appears that what's been happening on feature/ec lately
with a middleware failure has to do with a hardcoded PID in
the test code itself causing a profile file to exist when
its not expected to by the test...

Test code used a PID of 135 and based on how get_logfiles()
is written, any real PID that starts with 135 will cause a
false failure in test_call().  This can be seen via inspection
and confirmed in logfiles where all captured assertions show
a profile filename beginning with 135.  Tried getting smarter
about choosing a fake PID (int) but then decided it was 100%
safe to use 'ABC' for this test since that'll never show up!

Change-Id: I61adc36a127a5b362b2983f94c58dd9be3a9b13d

commit_message:
Avoid using deprecated Q_AGENT_EXTRA_AGENT_OPTS in ML2 setup

Q_AGENT_EXTRA_AGENT_OPTS is deprecated now and stack.sh displays
the warning that it will be removed early in "K" cycle.
Neutron ML2 devstack uses Q_AGENT_EXTRA_AGENT_OPTS to pass tunnel
configurations to Neutron plugin agents.

This commit removes the usage of Q_AGENT_EXTRA_AGENT_OPTS and
configures these config options directly.

Change-Id: I7fc1613ff78c0a8b1e80cc041b06f5d4680c34f2
Closes-Bug: #1354670

commit_message:
Set display name in apache processes

This change makes apache set process group name in the process name,
so when listing the processes the user can easily identify what's
running in each apache process. This is specially useful to debug
memory consumption or when a process consumming too much CPU.

Change-Id: I9787980052f451f452d3b8e5e51385ad5aa01e6a

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Allow cinder types to be created without be file

3rd party ci tests have not whitelisted errors:
"Not Whitelisted Volume type with name * could not be found."

These are creating noise. Instead of requiring a backend file
for each vendor, remove the if statement and just create the
necessary type for each defined back-end.

Change-Id: Ic88efa20eb53864e4f3d22d3306841797dcd118d

commit_message:
document multiple vCenter clusters support

- explicitly state that the Nova compute service can manage multiple
  ESX host clusters via single vCenter server
- update screenshot where vCenter hypervisor is selected, which shows
  how to specify multiple clusters
- remove limitation which states that single OpenStack environment can
  communicate with only one vCenter cluster

Implements: blueprint vcenter-documentation-update-fuel-5.1
Change-Id: I7da867f45b05c9d7dd0dbda31178f26422f49dc1

commit_message:
ec2: Add S3ImageMapping object

Add a nova object for another ID-UUID mapping used in the EC2 API.
This object will allow the removal of the last bit of direct db api
usage by the EC2 API code.

Part of blueprint convert-ec2-api-to-use-nova-objects

Change-Id: Icf84f2d5a50ce4c78ee7f51db8e6a2b0276afbb2

commit_message:
document new topology "Neutron with NSX"

- add image to Reference architecture that show how new topology looks
  like
- update screenshot that reflects new topology in environment creation
  wizard
- describe new topology in Planning guide
- in User guide mention that we have five available topologies
- explicitly state that separate Physical network is not required for
  "Neutron with NSX" topology

Implements: blueprint vcenter-documentation-update-fuel-5.1
Change-Id: I4b102e41713712c9cb6ce5603c3cd648cd0e9aab

Hi Jim,

I also have a theory why the check-tempest-dsvm-virtual-ironic is not passing, I've tried to deploy a machine with this patch applied locally and I noticed that the machine won't PXE boot.

Now, I think that's because the nova driver will update the node with the VIF information, but when it gets from the cache that info may not be there... so it fails to update neutron and the machine won't boot.

I'll dig a bit more, and let you know about my findings"}, {'account_id': 10343, 'date': '2014-08-13 17:23:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-13 17:23:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2014-08-14 09:06:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

Hi Jim,

(forget about my last theory, the reason why I got it to the PXE boot stage with this patch was because I killed N-CPU to speed up the resource tracker process... but that's where the problem lies)

I can confirm that the resource tracker is not getting updated when I have this patch in Ironic.

The thing is that the Ironic driver will only return the node as available to Nova after it has a valid power state[1], so if we cache the node before it have a valid power state the resource tracker will never be updated to show the available resources.

The cache in this patch also never gets old, so once cache it keep it forever, and that's another concern I have with this patch. Let's say we have a node in Ironic and we put it into maintenance mode, this should be reflect in Nova so that it remove that node from the resource tracker as available resources, but if we have it cached and the cache never gets updated even if we mark it as maintenance in Ironic for nova it will be always available.

So tho I think caching is a good thing here, I think we need a different approach for caching stuff here, with some cache invalidation mechanism etc...

[1] https://github.com/openstack/ironic/blob/master/ironic/nova/virt/ironic/driver.py#L168-L176

Thanks,
Lucas"}, {'account_id': 10343, 'date': '2014-08-14 13:59:11.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-14 13:59:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Query full node details and cache

Re-use this information to reduce a massive amount of queries to ironic
api to get info about individual nodes on the periodic task that syncs
resource usage.

Partial-Bug: 1357027

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-11 11:43:48.000000000', 'message': 'Enable filtering of credentials by user ID

A credentials entity has a user_id attribute. Currently the lack of a
filter of user_id means that we cannot use the keystone policy file to
enable users to have access to (only) their credentials. This fix solve
it by adding such a filter:

List credentials: `GET /credentials`
Optional query parameters:

commit_message:
Enable filtering of credentials by user ID

A credentials entity has a user_id attribute. Currently the lack of a
filter of user_id means that we cannot use the keystone policy file to
enable users to have access to (only) their credentials. This fix solves
it by adding such a filter:

List credentials: `GET /credentials`
Optional query parameters:
- `user_id` (string)

Implements: blueprint filter-credentials-by-user

Closes-Bug: #1267096

Change-Id: Iff016fac37b50d55d77ec7511aae4e57af34f08f

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-06-25 22:57:21.000000000', 'message': 'Rewrite ionice command filter using ChainingRegExpFilter

Currently, the ionice command prepended to a dd command is allowed by three
rootwrap RegExpFilter's that cover 3 arguments patterns. However, this
doesn't support if either 'iflag=direct' or 'oflag=direct' is omitted.
Because of this problem, deletion of volumes may fail if volume_clear_ionice
is set, as 'iflag=direct' is omitted.

This commit fixes this problem by replacing the filters with
ChainingRegExpFilter's, which allow to execute ionice to be combined with the
other allowed commands, including 'dd'.

Originally '-c[0-3]( -n[0-7])?' was allowed as an ionice option, but it is
invalid to specify -n[0-7] in a single option (for example, when '-c2 -n7'
is specified, ionice causes an error "invalid class argument: '2 -n7'").
In this patch, 2 filters are provided to cover the case only with -c option
and the case with both -c and -n options.

Change-Id: Ia074bf3244b7f010bd9e3b5e46c3152c1848f3d3
Signed-off-by: Tomoki Sekiyama <tomoki.sekiyama@hds.com>
Closes-Bug: 1334422

commit_message:
Rewrite ionice command filter using ChainingRegExpFilter

Currently, the ionice command prepended to a dd command is allowed by three
rootwrap RegExpFilter's that cover 3 arguments patterns. However, this
doesn't support if either 'iflag=direct' or 'oflag=direct' is omitted.
Because of this problem, deletion of volumes may fail if volume_clear_ionice
is set, as 'iflag=direct' is omitted.

This commit fixes this problem by replacing the filters with
ChainingRegExpFilter's, which allow to execute ionice to be combined with the
other allowed commands, including 'dd'.

Originally '-c[0-3]( -n[0-7])?' was allowed as an ionice option, but it is
invalid to specify -n[0-7] in a single option (for example, when '-c2 -n7'
is specified, ionice causes an error "invalid class argument: '2 -n7'").
In this patch, 2 filters are provided to cover the case only with -c option
and the case with both -c and -n options.

Change-Id: Ia074bf3244b7f010bd9e3b5e46c3152c1848f3d3
Signed-off-by: Tomoki Sekiyama <tomoki.sekiyama@hds.com>
Closes-Bug: 1334422

commit_message:
Revert "Use /opt/git instead of /opt/stack/new"

This reverts commit 0092a3dd8cf98248278c1c3d0963ccf2d3f1ea00.

We need to revert this change, it's causing our CI jobs to not
actually test the submitted patches.

I agree that in some cases the glance API could be used to create a tiny image a proper snapshot is not required, but you could do that for more tests that the ones you changed here.

My proposal would be to separate the two things.

commit_message:
Add new snapshot compute feature flag

Nova image creation / instance snapshotting is not supported across compute
drivers.   This adds a new compute feature flag and skips tests that attempt
to create snapshots.

Change-Id: I814157d434e3d5e13dfae9b9ee7d5135199c4e97

commit_message:
SecurityGroupRuleExists should point out rule id inseand of group id

When we get a SecurityGroupRuleExists, we want to get the rule id
instaed of group id, and this is what the fucntion
_check_for_duplicate_rules() does.

Change-Id: I9b526d9829582cb26bfda98bcaf1704fe8681cbe
Closes-bug:  #1354343

In wbatch fast mode, scripts are copied to the autostart directory but
they are never executed and therefore not removed from there. This patch
fixes that.

Change-Id: I33f2881a0fbe8b91038825b25aa8bcd79074786e
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs
'}]
commit_message:
labs: remove autostart files in fast wbatch mode

In wbatch fast mode, scripts are copied to the autostart directory but
they are never executed and therefore not removed from there. This patch
fixes that.

Change-Id: I33f2881a0fbe8b91038825b25aa8bcd79074786e
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs

Right now we are using XML docbook with maven building pdfs and html, following the lead of the documentation program. There has been some discussion around using ASCdoc or even pandoc. I'm not opposed to discussing it as a long term option, but it's not viable I think for the short term. Do you guys have any preferences?

We will also need the trainer preparation, tools, and day of instructions. Is that handy someplace?"}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2014-06-19 01:03:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

One practical concern around using RST is that this will not work with our translation machinery. Given the interest in non-English areas to run training such as this, I would see this as highly desirable.

Do you need assistance converting it to docbook?'}, {'account_id': 287, 'date': '2014-06-19 05:27:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

We should probably setup some time to discuss this further then. My initial thought was to store somewhere accessible and in an easy to hack format the slides we used in Atlanta. RST is very simple and seemed like a good solution. Docbook for what are just a few fairly simple slides seemed to me like too much work. Also, I don't see much value in using the translator's community to simply translate the slides: they could be easily re-done by local instructors, and the translation would probably be a good exercise for them. 

In any case, I'm ok with investigating the docbook toolchain (already asked Tom for help setting it up)."}, {'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2014-06-19 05:59:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I agree with Sean to try and use Docbook if possible to follow OpenStack manuals footsteps. Otherwise I dont see any drawback in using rst.'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2014-06-19 06:03:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

re-doing the format for every single language, and thereby creating separate unlinked versions with differing maintenance seems like a problem to me given the amount of updates this will require :) 

For example, if the current toolchain is used, changing an URL would not require any change to translated versions. If it is not used, each of these would need to be updated. Wording, or other trivial changes are highlighted to translators as being only a few percent changed, and a good guide provided to update them. Translation memories provide vocabulary reusable across every project in OpenStack, etc.

Learning how to deliver a course is significant work, and not using the existing toolchain would remove the support of our not insignificant translation community to assist.

Personally, I don't find docbook any more or less difficult than RST - the key is just to stick to the simple tags and ignore the crazy stuff.

I think we should take this offline."}, {'account_id': 2064, 'date': '2014-06-19 06:15:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Docbook is fine with me.'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2014-06-19 06:16:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I will concede though - since these are slides, docbook itemizedlists suck. I am looking to see if there is a better way of doing them.'}, {'account_id': 11109, 'date': '2014-06-19 06:18:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

We should not convert from rst to docbook while docs are considering moving into the opposite direction. Talk to Anne Gentle before taking a decision, she seems to be most involved in that discussion.'}, {'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2014-06-19 06:24:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Tom, we may need to develop/modify clouddocs plugin for making it better for slides or it would be a set of hacks around the docbook to deliver the slides with various features. I agree with the use of landslide or similar easy set of tools so devs can focus more on content.'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2014-06-19 06:31:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

The only concern I'm raising at this time is one of translation, since we have at least one community (Japan) strongly interested in this content. In addition, it seems likely that the content will have a high degree of use in other non-English-speaking areas. I'm no zealot :)"}, {'account_id': 6923, 'date': '2014-06-20 02:57:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
labs: option to set number of vCPUs for each node

Currently, all nodes get the default number of vCPUs (1). With this
patch, the number of vCPUs can be set in a node's configuration
file.

For the compute node, we set the number of vCPUs to 2.

Change-Id: I137be612bc6cb8f2d31adfd756404a9c6349e3c5
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs

commit_message:
Add Schema parent class for Property, Input, Output

Add a Schema class that handle all schema-related information
(description, type, constraints, required etc) of Property,
Input, Output.

Change-Id: Ic4e4e5e1a5fa29fc3d668c295d6b2ea85eecb0cd
Closes-Bug:#1349457

commit_message:
Use /opt/git instead of /opt/stack/new

The generalized repo caching mechanism in nodepool puts copies of
every repo in gerrit into /opt/git, which is an improvement over
the selective caching of some repos into ~jenkins/workspace-cache.
To support a cleaner move to a diskimage-builder version of
nodepool, migrate to consuming repos from /opt/git instead of
from /opt/stack/new.

/opt/git on nodepool images is owned by root.

This patch needs a change to the tripleO jobs to land (or a
similar patch to allow the jenkins user access to /opt/git)
in order to work.

Depends-On: Iebe3b5f194682e759266553b0f1e861f2958b048
Change-Id: Id35c2b99a889f2af2baa10351be21e136e2c5cd0

commit_message:
Guard for worlddump in case LOGDIR is undefined

If LOGDIR is undefined, we'll end up calling worldump with the `-d` option but
pass in an empty string as the option value. This causes an argument parsing
error inside worlddump.

The proposed fix is to detect if LOGDIR is undefined, and if so, omit the `-d`
argument.

Change-Id: I77968849ebd3e3bebd2e5929b87b60fc1b6541bf
Closes-Bug: 1333321

'}, {'created': '2014-07-28 11:58:49.000000000', 'message': 'Use opportunistic approach for migration testing

Refactored migration tests due to use OpportunisticTestCase, removed
unused code and ``test_migrations.conf`` file, minor migration scripts
cleanup.
This patch also add "forward compatibility" with the next version of oslo.db
- class BaseMigrationsTestCase was removed from master, so we should
avoid of it's usage.

This change allows tests use database ``openstack_citest`` only
for connection to the database backend. The main feature of this
approach is - for each migration test will be created new database
with random name. This will avoid migration tests of race conditions
and reduce tests intersection.
``test_migrations.conf`` file was removed, because we create test
database for migration test, so we no longer need test database
credentials.

Some migrations scripts was modified due to ensure, that they executed
with a single DB connection.

Change-Id: Ia503f01fdf2df00cce7212fcc9e0b6cc98ad6520
'}, {'created': '2014-07-31 08:56:40.000000000', 'message': 'Run migration tests on PostgreSQL and MySQL

Refactored migration tests due to use OpportunisticTestCase.
This change allows tests use database ``openstack_citest`` only
for connection to the database backend - for each migration test
will be created new database with a random name. This will avoid
migration tests of race conditions and reduce tests intersection.
Added MySQL-python and psycopg2 to test-requirements, because we need
some database connectors to run tests on PostgreSQL and MySQL.

``test_migrations.conf`` file was removed, because we create test
database for migration test, so we no longer need test database
credentials.

Some migrations scripts was modified due to ensure, that they executed
with a single DB connection.

Removed get_table() method - we cau use a similar function from
oslo.db.sqlalchemy.utils module.

This patch also add "forward compatibility" with the next version of oslo.db
- class BaseMigrationsTestCase was removed from master, so we should
avoid of it's usage and signature of method _walk_versions() from class
test_migrations.WalkVersionsMixin

Change-Id: Ia503f01fdf2df00cce7212fcc9e0b6cc98ad6520
'}, {'created': '2014-08-01 11:43:55.000000000', 'message': 'Run migration tests on PostgreSQL and MySQL

Refactored migration tests due to use OpportunisticTestCase.
This change allows tests use database ``openstack_citest`` only
for connection to the database backend - for each migration test
will be created new database with a random name. This will avoid
migration tests of race conditions and reduce tests intersection.
Added MySQL-python and psycopg2 to test-requirements, because we need
some database connectors to run tests on PostgreSQL and MySQL.

``test_migrations.conf`` file was removed, because we create test
database for migration test, so we no longer need test database
credentials.

Some migrations scripts was modified due to ensure, that they executed
with a single DB connection.

Removed get_table() method - we cau use a similar function from
oslo.db.sqlalchemy.utils module.

This patch also add "forward compatibility" with the next version of oslo.db

commit_message:
Run migration tests on PostgreSQL and MySQL

Refactored migration tests due to use OpportunisticTestCase.
This change allows tests use database ``openstack_citest`` only
for connection to the database backend - for each migration test
a new database, with a random name, will be created. This will avoid
migration tests of race conditions and reduce tests interaction.
Added MySQL-python and psycopg2 to test-requirements, because we need
some database connectors to run tests on PostgreSQL and MySQL.

``test_migrations.conf`` file was removed, because we create test
database for migration test, so we no longer need test database
credentials.

Some migrations scripts was modified to ensure, that they executed
with a single DB connection.

Removed get_table() method - we can use a similar function from
oslo.db.sqlalchemy.utils module.

This patch also add "forward compatibility" with the next version of oslo.db
- class BaseMigrationsTestCase was removed from master, so we should
avoid of it's usage and signature of method _walk_versions() from class
test_migrations.WalkVersionsMixin

Co-Authored-By: Roman Podoliaka <rpodolyaka@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: Ia503f01fdf2df00cce7212fcc9e0b6cc98ad6520

Allowing to have static x-axes in line chart

Allowing to define static time span for the line chart.

commit_message:
Use python convention for function names in test_notifications

Renamed a few methods in test_notifications to follow the python
convention, using underscores instead of camelCase.

Change-Id: I48003566b8f5967185e5067ff3cfbf4324b81d43

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-06-26 14:43:11.000000000', 'message': 'Add "rally info" command

Here we add a new "rally info" command, which, based on the input,
prints descriptions for different entities in Rally (in this patch -
benchmark scenarios & scenario groups, more entities are to follow
(deployment engines etc.). This command makes use of docstrings by
parsing them and printing them in CLI in human-readable form.

The command should be called as "rally info find --query=<query>".

Samples:

    $ rally info find --query=create_meter_and_get_stats
    CeilometerStats.create_meter_and_get_stats (benchmark scenario).

    Test creating a meter and fetching its statistics.

    Meter is first created and then statistics is fetched for the same
    using GET /v2/meters/(meter_name)/statistics.

    Parameters:
       	- name_length: length of generated (random) part of meter name
        - kwargs: contains optional arguments to create a meter

    $ rally info find --query=Authenticate
    Authenticate (benchmark scenario group).

    This class should contain authentication mechanism.

    For different types of clients like Keystone.

Change-Id: Icf3545c0666d99ab7fd0eaabce8bbe572834e485

commit_message:
Add "rally info" command

Here we add a new "rally info" command, which, based on the input,
prints descriptions for different entities in Rally (in this patch -
benchmark scenarios & scenario groups, more entities are to follow
(deployment engines etc.)). This command makes use of docstrings by
parsing them and printing them in CLI in human-readable form.

The command should be called as "rally info find <query>" (or, in case
of an explicit parameter setting, "rally info find --query=<query>").

Samples:

    $ rally info find create_meter_and_get_stats
    CeilometerStats.create_meter_and_get_stats (benchmark scenario).

    Test creating a meter and fetching its statistics.

    Meter is first created and then statistics is fetched for the same
    using GET /v2/meters/(meter_name)/statistics.

    Parameters:
        - name_length: length of generated (random) part of meter name
        - kwargs: contains optional arguments to create a meter

    $ rally info find Authenticate
    Authenticate (benchmark scenario group).

    This class should contain authentication mechanism.

    For different types of clients like Keystone.

Change-Id: Icf3545c0666d99ab7fd0eaabce8bbe572834e485

commit_message:
libvirt: convert cpu features attribute from list to a set

Currently, the cpu features list which is being sent to libvirt,
when creating a domain or calling compareCPU, must contain only
unique entries. Multiple issues arise when we are updating the
features attribute in LibvirtConfigCPU class (for example during
migration).

This change will change the features attribute from being a list
to a set. This make the LibvirtConfigCPU class keep only unique
features.
Adjusting the LibvirtConfigCPUFeature class to support set
operations by overriding the __eq__, __ne__ and __hash__
methods.

Closes-Bug: #1303536
Change-Id: I6350fe0e827c860aea77cc4fe56f18f5c1483580
Cherry-pick-x: 60c899b9da8d64b4a5979b69c43c77ed9d5bf248
