commit_message:
Allow to specify an empty package list in pkg_map

An empty package list can be provided in a pkg_map file for those
cases were there is no need to install the package.

Change-Id: I0df8c6848ec4ac9e0f90790f14e8eb5399650339

override the pbr-generated version. Unfortunately, this change breaks devstack
deployments. So the version attribute was added back to setup.cfg. Now

commit_message:
Update versionbuild script to handle setup.cfg version

The versionbump script used to supply a monotonically increasing version for
rpm packages was modified to supply a 'version=' attribute to setup.cfg, to
override the pbr-generated version. Unfortunately, this change breaks devstack
deployments. So the version attribute was added back to setup.cfg. Now
versionbump functionality needs to be reverted back to adding the timestamp to
the hard-coded version stamp, but with the more Pythonic mods suggested in the
previous CR.

Closes-Bug: #1358455
Change-Id: Icc5a6a4319ea4517f2812168f25840253eb50e28

PureISCSIDriver had some error logging messages that make use of empty
replacement fields "{}" in strings on which the .format() method is
called, as allowed in Python 2.7+. Python 2.6 requires explicitly
naming or enumerating fields, i.e., "{}" must be replaced with "{0}".
This change fixes this so PureISCSIDriver is Python 2.6 compatible.

PureISCSIDriver.terminate_connection() also changed to catch

commit_message:
Fix exception handling in PureISCSIDriver

PureISCSIDriver had some error logging messages that make use of empty
replacement fields "{}" in strings on which the .format() method is
called, as allowed in Python 2.7+. Python 2.6 requires explicitly
naming or enumerating fields, i.e., "{}" must be replaced with "{0}".
This change fixes this so PureISCSIDriver is Python 2.6 compatible.

PureISCSIDriver.terminate_connection() also changed to catch
errors raised by _get_host_name(). Exception handling generally changed
to be more correct.

This change also adds testing of these code path to the unit tests,
to make sure it's actually correct.

Change-Id: I84179a8bc59dcf5593664ab11c90b07c451fd360
Closes-Bug: 1357004

commit_message:
Update DevStack guide when querying the image UUID

The command to query the UUID of the default image to be deployed
was retuning more than one UUID because of a grep problem, that would
also cause the "nova boot" command to fail because it was passing more
arguments that expected.

This commit fix the regex to query the UUID of the image by ignoring
what comes after the name of the image.

Change-Id: I03ad610fdd3313977b61d0d82bd1b33811f7ece1

commit_message:
Change OS_REGION to OS_REGION_NAME

Dolph made a comment a while back saying region_name should be
region which I did.  Talked with Dean about this and he dug
his heels in saying it should be region_name.  All the CLIs
are using region_name.

Change-Id: I212eb4ec96a59650226ae5f5b0172c40c25dec90

commit_message:
use MissingParameterValue exception in iboot

The iboot driver raises InvalidParameterValue exception in _parse_driver_info() when any required parameters are missing. It should be raising
MissingParameterValue instead.

Change-Id: I7e8955712c0ef0166a1b4daf1008579413fdfcb1
Closes-Bug: #1358758

[{'created': '2014-08-19 15:40:22.000000000', 'message': "Add auth and remote connections support to MongoDB

Add options to provide admin user login and
password to be used while managing databases
and users.

Admin user should have at least permissions
'root' and 'restore'.

If there is no admin user mongo will work
in 'localhost exception' mode allowing
administration from the local interface.

Closes-Bug: 1354494

Change-Id: I253ee50523fba66586e7a42a7f0772adebe96e83
"}]
commit_message:
Add auth and remote connections support to MongoDB

Add options to provide admin user login and
password to be used while managing databases
and users.

Admin user should have at least permissions
'root' and 'restore'.

If there is no admin user mongo will work
in 'localhost exception' mode allowing
administration from the local interface.

Closes-Bug: 1354494

Change-Id: I253ee50523fba66586e7a42a7f0772adebe96e83

commit_message:
Fix error in example of an RPC server

Sample code in the documentation for rpc.server has an error which
prevents the code from being run. Replacing the `self` with `None`
results in code that runs. Whether it does anything useful is
an open question.

Change-Id: I81391fa3efdc65d54ca3aa155d63584f2b6f98c2

[{'created': '2014-08-15 20:23:48.000000000', 'message': "Fix test_upload_volume* failure on environment without /dev/loop1

Unit tests test_upload_volume* in test_image_utils.py fail if the test
environment doesn't have /dev/loop1, because it actually calls os.stat
for the source file. This fixes the error by mocking os.stat.

In addition, currently stat_result class in the test_image_utils.py are
not set as return_value for mocked os.stat. It also adds the settings.

Change-Id: I55700c363ab578ce5a47cb326424f5986ff388e9
Closes-Bug: 1357521
"}]
commit_message:
Fix test_upload_volume* failure on environment without /dev/loop1

Unit tests test_upload_volume* in test_image_utils.py fail if the test
environment doesn't have /dev/loop1, because it actually calls os.stat
for the source file. This fixes the error by mocking os.stat.

In addition, currently stat_result class in the test_image_utils.py are
not set as return_value for mocked os.stat. It also adds the settings.

Change-Id: I55700c363ab578ce5a47cb326424f5986ff388e9

Update volume client check success

Updated all volume tests to remove the response checks
and move to respective clients.

Partially Implements blueprint: client-checks-success

commit_message:
Update the config reference tables

Include the new tables in the documentation.

Fix the cinder-prophetstor_dpl.xml filename and the xiv category.

Manually fix those files for niceness test:
- glance-logging.xml (lines 34, 38), fixed in oslo-incubator
- trove-logging.xml (lines 26, 30), fixed in oslo-incubator
- neutron-openvswitch_agent.xml (line 45), to be fixed in neutron

commit_message:
Add glossary entries for Arch Design

Add new entries: north-south traffic, east-west traffic and TripleO.

Add entries for these terms to the Arch Design Guide. Use consistent
spelling for these entries.
Include some edits for improved wording.

Change-Id: Ic241664a44c0e41e3961206b626eef2acb0c5b31

commit_message:
Use request latency to calculate throughput

The current code uses the duration for the entire test to calculate
throughput. However, we are really interested in how long the requests
themselves took, minus the overhead of the benchmark tool itself. To
that end, this patch changes the throughput calculation to use the
total latency added up for just the HTTP requests.

Change-Id: I162101f9bfd1512de0e98f31764c428f314ef5ad

[{'created': '2014-08-14 20:46:27.000000000', 'message': "Server IP resource

The server IP resource can only list.  The Resource.list method
needed to be overridden because:
* The url path contains the server_id.
* The output is a dict of networks rather than an array.

Also in this change:
* ServerIP objects have sufficient information to stand on their
  own because they contain the server_id and network_label.
* An ips(session) convenience method has been added to the Server.
* The list example has been updated to pass data to path_args so
  the list method and format the url.

The path_args parameter to list may be convenient for other
classes.  I didn't add it to the Resource.list method because
that isn't required for this change.

Change-Id: Iac77aba144d2e5b4ca4cdbf97e534d83519066ef
"}]
commit_message:
Server IP resource

The server IP resource can only list.  The Resource.list method
needed to be overridden because:
* The url path contains the server_id.
* The output is a dict of networks rather than an array.

Also in this change:
* ServerIP objects have sufficient information to stand on their
  own because they contain the server_id and network_label.
* An ips(session) convenience method has been added to the Server.
* The list example has been updated to pass data to path_args so
  the list method and format the url.

The path_args parameter to list may be convenient for other
classes.  I didn't add it to the Resource.list method because
that isn't required for this change.

Change-Id: Iac77aba144d2e5b4ca4cdbf97e534d83519066ef

commit_message:
Get EC2 snapshot mappings with nova object

Use the EC2SnapshotMapping nova object for getting the mapping instead
of directly using the db API.

Part of blueprint convert-ec2-api-to-use-objects

Change-Id: I258ffe0a3fe3b0d7b2524bb64f1137127731bdd5

Previously, neutron would return a 404 error when attaching a subnet
to a router where the router did not exist in nsx. In this case
we should not return a 404 but instead succeed and set the router

commit_message:
NSX: router-interface-add returns 404 if router not found in nsx

Previously, neutron would return a 404 error when attaching a subnet
to a router where the router did not exist in nsx. In this case
we should not return a 404 but instead succeed and set the router
port status to error same as we do in the case when create ports
on networks that do not exist in nsx.

Change-Id: I5aef9ae5968a1fc955f01317bc99f17e96cdc407
Closes-bug: #1292192

[{'created': '2014-08-15 05:21:21.000000000', 'message': "Make auth plugins dest save to os_

If the auth plugin saves into the normal namespace like .user_id and
user_id is an argument of the command then the two argument collide with
each other.

This is fairly common, particularly in keystoneclient's shell.

There is a little bit of a compatibility concern in that the variables
on the returned namespace have changed, however the usage of this
function should be if you use register_argparse_arguments you should
also use load_from_argparse_arguments and that is not changed.

Change-Id: Id1cb0983a1e78661492acd78ad9aa67ff8d49250
"}]
commit_message:
Make auth plugins dest save to os_

If the auth plugin saves into the normal namespace like .user_id and
user_id is an argument of the command then the two argument collide with
each other.

This is fairly common, particularly in keystoneclient's shell.

There is a little bit of a compatibility concern in that the variables
on the returned namespace have changed, however the usage of this
function should be if you use register_argparse_arguments you should
also use load_from_argparse_arguments and that is not changed.

Change-Id: Id1cb0983a1e78661492acd78ad9aa67ff8d49250

commit_message:
Add ability to manage Neutron ML2 plugin package state

Introduce the package_ensure parameter to add the ability
to manage Neutron ML2 plugin package state.

Closes-bug: #1355370
Change-Id: I3bf6ed68015c13cf61db1b43dfbf4fd3c845d00f

commit_message:
Remove unused db api methods

Remove methods that are no longer used from the db API.  New methods
were created that replaced these when the EC2SnapshotMapping object
was created in earlier commits.

Related to blueprint convert-ec2-api-to-use-nova-objects

Change-Id: I5431dd34d6a3fcea687b9d8f192a822e83ed9402

commit_message:
Add EC2SnapshotMapping object

Create a nova object for the mappings between snapshot UUIDs and the
corresponding EC2 ID.

Part of blueprint convert-ec2-api-to-use-nova-objects

Change-Id: Ie29db77e404faff6ab9f12877094ea042e3c9924

commit_message:
BGP dynamic routing: add association with entities

BGP basic goal is expose a Neutron API endpoint to let advertise and
discover routes from/to uplink peers.

AdvertiseRoute extends Route and is used to advertise routes through a
routing peer. As ExtraRoutes does with the Router entity, this
functionality is available through the update_routingpeer method. So
advertise routes are modified altogether.

A new binding between routing peer and router is added. The associated
router will be the entity that will 'learn' discovered routes from uplinks.

Change-Id: Ib13934b749270fc2cda7178cd2a81a8805d6eb8d
Partially-Implements: blueprint bgp-dynamic-routing

commit_message:
Fixes an issue with the XMLEquals matcher

The matcher implementation would fail to match two documents that are
semantically equivalent, but sibling elements appear in different
document order.

Change-Id: I99dc6401e73be4c61bb265c3258b6245f2e7bb34
Closes-bug: #1347891

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-18 22:04:06.000000000', 'message': "Recover from errors while deleting image segments

When Glance attempts to delete an image, which is stored as a
segmented object, if an error occurs while deleting one of the
segments, delete operation fails while leaving behind rest of
the segments.

This patch enables Glance to recover from one or more errors during
segment deletion and proceed with deleting other segments. However,
this patch doesn't do anything with the failed segments themselves.
With this patch it'd be possible that even after an image is
deleted, certain chunks are left behind in the store.

Change-Id: Id1dde6655f48672a9b9f1253a6980ca7a9402db2
Closes-Bug: 1256364
"}]
commit_message:
Recover from errors while deleting image segments

When Glance attempts to delete an image, which is stored as a
segmented object, if an error occurs while deleting one of the
segments, delete operation fails while leaving behind rest of
the segments.

This patch enables Glance to recover from one or more errors during
segment deletion and proceed with deleting other segments. However,
this patch doesn't do anything with the failed segments themselves.
With this patch it'd be possible that even after an image is
deleted, certain chunks are left behind in the store.

Change-Id: Id1dde6655f48672a9b9f1253a6980ca7a9402db2
Closes-Bug: 1256364

commit_message:
Use EC2SnapshotMapping for creating mappings

Use the EC2SnapshotMapping nova object to create the mappings instead
of using the db api directly.

Part of blueprint convert-ec2-api-to-use-nova-objects

Change-Id: If280b1061185faf71c632a7bc4a8530346c18c97

commit_message:
Update compute driver macs_for_instance per docs

Updates the docstring for the macs_for_instance method
to match the documented Nova driver.

Also updates the method to return values per the docs.

Change-Id: I87f36ab675f57137f46416fa810eda5662d92ee0

commit_message:
Objectify association in neutronapi

This makes the neutronapi use the Instance object for the associate
path and updates the test to match.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects-juno

Change-Id: I045bfbd16e3b45107bd11e3874ce47280574930a

commit_message:
LHS assignment expressions didn't work with non-trivial indexation

Most of assignment expressions involving indexation operator except
for the most trivial one fail.

For example the following failed:

$myDict[$keyName]: value
$myDict['A']['B']: value (even if $myDict['A'] is a dictionary)
$myList[2 + 2]: value
$myList[$index]: value

This commit adds support for sub-expressions within LHS-expressions

Change-Id: I4b72e85b5f9bda04c6156d5c8b07eb8f5358643d
Closes-Bug: #1358545

Apache sometimes is slow to release the port which can cause restarts of apache
to fail due to the requested port already being bound. Make use of the function
'restart_apache_server' added to fix #1342256, which introduces a small sleep

commit_message:
Make apache restarts a little more forgiving

Apache sometimes is slow to release the port which can cause restarts of apache
to fail due to the requested port already being bound. Make use of the function
'restart_apache_server' added to fix #1342256, which introduces a small sleep
between the stop and start to help make apache deployments a bit more resilient.

Closes-Bug: #1358281

Change-Id: Ic4206f24d7bb04b014b3cb179d2303bb301c59d2

commit_message:
Improve benchmarking tool

This commit adds several enhancements to benchmarking tool: server_url
and path to messages now can be configured in config file.  Default
output of program has been changed: now it prints values in json so they
can be parsed more easily. Previous human readable representation is
accessible via --verbose flag.

The `total_requests` metric now shows all performed requests (either
failed or successful) and new metric - `successful_requests` - was
introduced to store count of successful requests.

Change-Id: Id6fe4b2046394a348ba07eb5b2b003c6024b78b0
Partially-implements: blueprint gen-bench-reports

Clean up devstack plugin after LVM driver removal

Devstack plugin has some logic, specific to LVM driver,
due to removal of LVM driver this logic can and should be removed.

Partially implements blueprint remove-lvm-driver

commit_message:
labs: quotation marks around variables

It is generally a good idea to keep variables within quotation marks,
even if we don't expect the value to ever contain whitespace.

Also, it makes automated test tools (shellcheck) happy.

Change-Id: I1c323a1dd10087694312892eac3c11cf54e07ce4

This has been brought up in IRC a couple times, so leaving a response closer to the actual code:

In the original patch this type of solution was discussed. The way I see it there are two use cases this file should cater to - a developer running a standard devtest (which works fine with a static number) and someone trying to do something of a larger scale using purely vm's (note that a production setup does not use this). In the latter case, I do not see any reason that building a special testenv (or at a minimum defining a property to statically set size of your testenv) is a problem - you are running a non-standard developer setup.

Additionally, tying hardware definitions directly to scaling requirements is not a realistic setup and I would argue actually moves us further away from devtest emulating a production setup."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-05-26 21:17:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

- gate-tripleo-incubator-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/97/93597/6/check/gate-tripleo-incubator-docs/ad91393/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 34s'}, {'account_id': 7579, 'date': '2014-05-27 11:49:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6969, 'date': '2014-05-28 09:07:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1

I echo Jan and JP's comments. 

I need to set OVERCLOUD_COMPUTESCALE to 20 for developer testing as we are know to hit problems at this scale so the ability to test and developer at this level with VM's is a must."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-05-29 06:24:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

Michael, you can export NODE_CNT=20 and it will do what you want.

@JP - the check you add is still in the wrong layer. I suggest checking instead in devtest_overcloud.sh for having enough hypervisor resources to run the desired test.

Consider scale-up scenarios where the machine count will increase over time - thats precisely the complex modelling we *don't want* to have to maintain. Separate layers are useful, and this is a separate layer issue.

As I understand it the issues this patch is crafted to fix include:
 - you find out 'late' (e.g. 15m later) that there are not enough machines to deploy your cloud to.
 - you have no way of querying how many machines will be needed before you run the scripts, so calculating what NODE_CNT should be is hard.

Have I missed other cases?

Both of these things seem to be real issues for folk with real hardware, not exclusively the realm of test vms' - so we should solve both of them for our production users.

Uncovering these sorts of issue is one of the things that we wanted to achieve by making the vm test layer closer to real hardware."}, {'account_id': 215, 'date': '2014-05-29 08:29:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

@lifeless - moving the check into devtest_overcloud seems reasonable, but as usual your timings are heavily optimistic.  I would estimate that to be at least 30 minutes later.  Thats 30 minutes for each developer if they make a mistake and do not set NODE_CNT to a value that is large enough for the *SCALE variables.  That will get more complex once HA lands for the undercloud, as there would likely be another variable controller the undercloud scale.

For the regular developer use-case you are then requiring an extra environment variable to be set - something that your previous reviews has suggested is undesirable.  I just want to point out the different standards you are applying to different patches here.

In summary, I think this change should still be acceptable as-is, and that an enhancement could be made in the undercloud/overcloud scripts to validate that the testenv.json file is large enough for our purposes.

I do not think that the issue fixed by this patch is a valid one, it is a contrived issue created by a bug in a previous patch.'}, {'account_id': 215, 'date': '2014-05-29 08:30:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 6969, 'date': '2014-05-29 09:59:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

@lifeless but can't the CI just NODE_CNT=15. I use OVERCLOUD_COMPUTESCALE variable to control all this and it has worked fine. Now I am responsible for NODE_CNT and with changes to the CONTROLSCALE coming and ha I am likely to get this wrong.

Even your maths is wrong. It should be NODE_CNT=20 + seed + undercloud + 1 controller for now maybe more in the future.

For all you have gone on about the UI of devtest this seems hard to fathom. Any developer coming to this in the future and if they run into this limit will have to know about this, if and when I move to a new machine I will have to remember to set this up correctly.

Another solution is instead of pushing this down to devtest_overcloud and waiting for it to fail is to push it up into devtest.sh I don't belive the ci uses this, so if you call devtest.sh then it will calculate NODE_CNT correctly and override devtest_testenv which we can leave alone. This will work for me."}, {'account_id': 10035, 'date': '2014-05-29 17:48:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

@Michael: 20 + seed + undercloud +1 controller implies you have 20 compute nodes and are using _testenv to define them? The simple solution is to pick a high enough number, so if you really have 20 compute nodes defined this way (which seems surprising) just pick a value of 30. For most use cases it seems like 15.. or 20 even more so would suffice.

We seem to all be vigorously agreeing that this patch prevents a user from defining too small a number of testenv vm's, which is trivial to do otherwise. The problem is that is desired behavior for this system (as said before, this is a problem faced by users of real hardware) and adding auto scaling the number of nodes defined at this level would emulate something for testenv vm's which is not replicated for users of real hardware. Given that the sole purpose of this setup is to emulate the use case of real-hardware users, this is an issue."}, {'account_id': 215, 'date': '2014-05-29 18:08:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

it is supposed to be the easy way of getting tripleo working

this is the use-case of novice or new developers

so the workflow end-to-end with devtest.sh should be easy and work

as you become knowledgable with the tools you use them individually to perform more advanced testing

so as you become more proficient you would create your own test environment and test these failure cases with a view to improving the corner cases that can affect users

this is what is documented within the scripts themselves, and in the wiki documentation

Change Icff5e728148f2744f3fc7c6e99d744be9fda180b set the number of
nodes created for a test environment to a fixed value for reasons
that were not well explained in the commit message.

This effectively broke the ability of the OVERCLOUD_*SCALE variables
to operate correctly and also created a large number of VMs on
developer workstations unnecessarily.

This sets the value back to being determined from the other variables
as is appropriate.

It also allows overriding of the value by setting NODE_CNT in the
calling environment, as reading comments in the previous change it
seems the reason for setting it to a fixed number was for TripleoCI
purposes.  My opinion is that the TripleCI scripts are the appropriate
place to fix values, and that these user/developer-focused scripts
should remain correct for users/developers without requiring an extra
arbitrary variable to be set to match actions of environment creation
to their previously expressed desire through the use of
OVERCLOUD_*SCALE variables.

Closes-bug: 1319473
Change-Id: I93c09e1905ca4eb6e9e580ecd0e9d4b8fcf1339e

commit_message:
Provide useful error early if not enough nodes

Change Icff5e728148f2744f3fc7c6e99d744be9fda180b set the number of
nodes created for a test environment to a fixed value.

Document the reason for the change, and also error early if not enough
nodes are created, so that we don't unnecessarily waste developer time
debugging the failure of an overcloud deploy due to lack of resources.

Change-Id: I93c09e1905ca4eb6e9e580ecd0e9d4b8fcf1339e

commit_message:
ec2: Use S3ImageMapping object

Use the S3ImageMapping in the EC2 API to remove the last bit of direct
db API usage.

Part of blueprint convert-ec2-api-to-use-nova-objects.

Change-Id: I7d66a4d05f42ffd854afe21024c88b096aeaaeaa

commit_message:
Fix py3k-unsafe code in test_get_properties()

This changes the unit test test_get_properties() so that it is
py3k-safe.

This is a follow-up to a comment in review 107092:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/107092/8/ironic/tests/drivers/test_ipmitool.py

commit_message:
Resolved server and instance status redundancy

Instance and server resource's _check_active() methods were
stripping off an extra '(STATUS)' string from the status.
This change moves the code of consistently handling status
to the nova client in heat. So, both the resources need not
perform any exra stuff to determine the status.

Change-Id: Ib527c001a2cdae90de1545ccdd56ad722c724d07

commit_message:
Fix Neutron core_plugin selection and NSX_OVS installation

* Add if statement for NSX
* Fix a string substitution in plugin_neutronnsx/manifests/alter_neutron_server.pp
* Run plugin_neutronnsx::install_ovs in Stage 'netconfig' to avoid circular dependancies

Change-Id: Iac46b79dae54a90b96ae8af7709a5d5676e7e95b
Closes-bug: #1358255

(1 comment)

Question about what the expected behavior is if more than one snapshot is triggered - I assumed it would be possible for a stack to have more than one snapshot, but the resource implementation seems to indicate that only one is possible, otherwise we'll overwrite the ID and leak a snapshot on delete_snapshot.

Maybe I'm missing something, can you describe what's expected in this situation - do we enforce only one snapshot per stack at the top level?"}, {'account_id': 7385, 'date': '2014-08-19 14:01:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-08-19 14:20:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

Ok, removing my objection, but this is quite a confusing model IMO, so perhaps could benefit from some additional comments and/or docs in the future.

My understanding having dug more into the code is:

1. service.py triggers the stack snapshot
2. service.py creates the abandon data, which includes the snapshot ID's of the things being snapshotted
3. a snapshot record is created/updated containing the abandon data
4. On delete, we iterate over the snapshot records and use the resource delete function to handle deleting the various snapshots

Is that about right?  Is so then my assumption we'll leak snapshots is wrong, but it's a bit of a convoluted process."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-19 14:20:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15: -Verified

commit_message:
Adds KMIPSecretStore and unit tests

This adds a KMIP implementation of SecretStore. This implementation will use
a KMIP server backend to store secrets. Additionally, this patch adds unit
tests that are in a format similar to the rest of the OpenStack projects.

Implements the SecretStore abstraction from:
    https://review.openstack.org/#/c/94710/

Change-Id: Id39b6c84d0990369e2f535f22826cd41708a2f63
Implements blueprint kmip-secret-store

commit_message:
Disable hacking rule H305

This commit disables the H305 rule because it is inconsistent between
python releases. Additionally while the logical grouping is a good
thing in most cases it can be excessive to enforce sometimes. Having
reviewers attempt to catch it in most cases should be sufficient.

Change-Id: I7530fe2295c4260a20f8cdd1f853611a9a6b2f99

commit_message:
Replace horizon alerting with an angular one

    Horizon alerting is now fully integrated into the angular
application. The object horizon.msg is available in the application
in order to keep the compatibility, it is a link to the new angular
service object.

Change-Id: If52b364eb8f3c0976bd1799a806db1a67431b5f5
Implements: blueprint horizon-angular

commit_message:
engine service add owner_id to create_stack

Adds owner_id as an optional argument to the top-level interface for
handling stack-creates, so it will be possible to create a nested stack
via an RPC call between engines.

Change-Id: I319e0d906d6ad54da6ce782a8a9dd9704f40e225
blueprint: decouple-nested

commit_message:
Partial oslo-incubator sync -- log.py

This patch pulls in the changes in openstack/common/log.py that fix
a problem exposed by the removal of translation from LOG.debug
messages.  This removal causes the messages to no longer be unicode, which
can cause formatting problems.  The changes in log.py ensure that any
message that is not of six.test_type is coverted to six.text_type.

Note that this is required to complete blueprint: i18n-enablement.

Generated with:
python update.py --base nova --dest-dir /opt/stack/nova --modules log

log:
 759bd87 Merge "Set keystonemiddleware and routes.middleware to log on WARN l
 71d072f Merge "Except socket.error if syslog isn't running"
 37c0091 Add unicode coercion of logged messages to ContextFormatter
 6614413 Correct coercion of logged message to unicode
 1188d88 Except socket.error if syslog isn't running
 ac995be Fix E126 pep8 errors
 36e5c2d Merge "Adjust oslo logging to provide adapter is enabled for"
 631f880 Set keystonemiddleware and routes.middleware to log on WARN level
 726d00a Adjust oslo logging to provide adapter is enabled for

Change-Id: I255a68fc60963386e8fefe65c3ffd269795adbf4
Closes-Bug: 1348244

commit_message:
Get rid of overspecification in vm.xml.

We don't need to pass the appropriate qemu binary into the vm template,
as libvirt will inject the proper one for us.  Similarly, we don't need
to tell libvirt what specific model of PC hardware to emulate, because
it will pick one that is appropriate to the devices we specify.

Change-Id: Id3762cce9b2ba9f96c1e7e79fad9a4bf8770bf7a

commit_message:
Adding configuration options for Swift proxy user

This change adds a new configuration option and functions for a Swift
proxy user. This user will be used as a delegate for trusts involving
accessing Swift objects. In the absence of a proxy user, the default
admin user will be used.

Changes
* adding entries for Swift proxy user in sahara.conf.sample
* adding keystone functions to get a proxy user client
* renaming older admin based client functions
* adding base method for admin and proxy keystone client acquisition

Partial-implements: blueprint edp-swift-trust-authentication
Change-Id: I62ba89778e3faa0041823a54e96d3af0f6c5c66a

commit_message:
Install of a Barbican RPM fails due to missing keystonemiddleware

keystonemiddleware (a dependency added recently) is not yet in RDO but
is a dependency for Barbican, and therefore needs to be FPM-ed via the
rpmbuild/package_dependencies.sh script.

Closes-Bug: #1356574
Change-Id: Iab1879d5529b45ddcfdb28224cba55fdd06d0205

commit_message:
Set rabbit_use_ssl to a configurable attribute

Add ability to enable rabbit_use_ssl item can be configured,
and not only set false value, so make glance support ssl.

Change-Id: I36ef4676f408d1b40994988a8730ea23cbf3be5e
Closes-Bug: #1358138

commit_message:
Add modify_horizon_config script

* Force writing this script even if package
  have removed it.
* Also set onlyif and unless for modify_config execs.

commit_message:
Prevent tenant viewing volumes owed by another

Bug introduced by 0505bb268942534ad5d6ecd5e34a4d9b0e7f5c04 allows any
tenant to get the details of a volume belonging to any other tenant
if the UUID is known.

This commit allows only the tenant or an admin to get a volume.

Change-Id: I0268d374f7529d89068dcbf3c1cb9ab3d60d4115
Closes-Bug: #1356368

commit_message:
Add workaround for reloading haproxy on Fedora

We want to be able to reload haproxy, but the upstream service file
for haproxy fails when we do.  This overwrites the upstream service
file with a fixed one that will eventually be added to the upstream
package.

Change-Id: I63bca52d7601850de87456fbb221a8400c6933aa
Related-Bug: 1348931

I however am holding off on +A in case anyone wants to weigh in before it goes in (don't want to sneak things in when people are asleep)"}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2014-08-15 16:07:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

I'm mixed about this.  I think it might be the wrong direction to say "/auth/"  any thing that happens after a token should be known a-priori.

THis information should be certainly communicated in the token response somehow.  It might also make sense to have these urls part of the token itself.  I'm less convinced that we want to make it a standard that you hack more things onto the auth url to do additional operations.

The one thing that might make sense to add to the auth url is some indication of the mechanism.  If a user gets and auth url and does a GET on it, it should return enough information that the user could then figure out how to get a token from it.  This means:

1.  The /auth suburl should not be protected via Kerberos, nor require client side certificates.  HTTPS is viable.

2.  /auth should return a list of supported mechanisms as well as the formats for the authentication information.  A return link with /auth/tokens  does make sense here.  /auth/projects and /auth/domains, while not harmful, are not really required, as that information could be done from other urls.  I'm not saying it shouldn't, just that it doesn't need to be there.


I think that if we return the links from /auth,  then the above spec is fine.  But the same could be done from the endpoint.  What is key is knowing where to find the data, and not the url itself.'}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2014-08-18 01:11:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

> THis information should be certainly communicated in the token response somehow. It might also make sense to have these urls part of the token itself. I'm less convinced that we want to make it a standard that you hack more things onto the auth url to do additional operations.

I was thinking the plan was to add less to the token here. In this case it should be mostly ok, because we want to add these routes to unscoped tokens. I don't disagree with this but its a part of a larger, everything should be linked from somewhere policy.

> The one thing that might make sense to add to the auth url is some indication of the mechanism. If a user gets and auth url and does a GET on it, it should return enough information that the user could then figure out how to get a token from it. This means:

> 1. The /auth suburl should not be protected via Kerberos, nor require client side certificates. HTTPS is viable.

Agreed, the only thing that should be protected by kerberos by default is the requesting a token. Everything once you have a token should use the token for authentication (until we land on a good strategy for indicating binding)

> 2. /auth should return a list of supported mechanisms as well as the formats for the authentication information. A return link with /auth/tokens does make sense here. /auth/projects and /auth/domains, while not harmful, are not really required, as that information could be done from other urls. I'm not saying it shouldn't, just that it doesn't need to be there.

I feel we are going to need this soon anyway. I've also wondered for horizon or such if a route that returned the responses from /auth/projects and /auth/domains in one hit is useful but i didn't want to put it at /auth. 

> I think that if we return the links from /auth, then the above spec is fine. But the same could be done from the endpoint. What is key is knowing where to find the data, and not the url itself.

I think this is a noble idea but one that we are not ready for yet. To use our API you have must know where the endpoints are located. It would be nice if JSON home fixed that for us but it's too early to tell."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-18 01:11:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: -Verified

commit_message:
fix: test_os_svc_daemon.py

Since I6487d0726db08912eed3062dfee2552940eadcfb, a ExecStartPre call
is added in the systemd .service file.
This patch adjust test_os_svc_daemon.py.

For the record, the remaining PEP8 error is fixed in
If5068ef77d6643c19de36bfcf4b4bf790f86b538.

Change-Id: I9b1859f9fc5846c7c42606644231105618e1a1a0

This also removes support for using Samba's "net conf", which can be a better way to manage smb.conf settings than just re-writing the configuration file, because there are not the same race conditions, and it can be made to replicate across a CTDB cluster (if that is ever implemented). 

Shouldn't CIFSNetConfHelper be brought back to generic.py before this is removed?'}, {'account_id': 8851, 'date': '2014-08-06 06:07:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

xing-yang,

glusterfs driver see light to become multitenant and there are some work on it. LVM driver won't be multitenant and while we have it we should make some support of it.

Andrew Bartlett,

Using "net conf" in generic driver seems to be a good idea, but it is defitinetely not related to this commit.

Samba's "net conf" can be used on host where it is installed, we do not use hosts of Manila services for shares with other drivers, so, it is unneeded with deletion of LVM driver.'}, {'account_id': 8851, 'date': '2014-08-06 12:09:20.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-06 12:09:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Regarding some questions about removing of single tenant drivers -- that is NOT the goal here. Single tenant drivers are okay. The intent here is to remove the code that overlaps cinder.

I'm blocking this change because I realized that we can't start using the generic driver in our gate until we have an image that's smaller than 300MB for the generic driver's nova instances.

I still want the work to go forward, but it needs to depend on fixing the generic image to get it to a size that the gate can deal with."}, {'account_id': 12808, 'date': '2014-08-07 05:50:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I'm a bit new here, but wanted to give a clue on image size.  If the current image uses Samba 3.6, an upgrade of the OS to one with Samba 4.x will greatly reduce Samba's on-disk size, as we moved to shared libraries with our new build system in 4.0.

Andrew Bartlett
(Samba Team)"}, {'account_id': 2417, 'date': '2014-08-07 16:12:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 8851, 'date': '2014-08-07 16:21:55.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-07 16:21:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Remove LVM driver

Support of LVM driver is planned to be dropped as it is duplicates
functionality from Cinder. Default driver is Generic driver, that uses Cinder.

Changes:
- removed LVM driver
- removed related stuff to LVM driver

Partially implements blueprint remove-lvm-driver
Change-Id: If2df592db082fdc5d609a5ce644106fee7d0583d

commit_message:
Remove cinder-volume from controller image.

The cinder-volume element will be installed as dep by either
cinder-tgt or cinder-lio. We do not want it to be deployed on the
controller nodes if one opts to use external BlockStorage nodes
and as such does not use cinder-{tgt,lio} on the controller.

Change-Id: I3d8f1af2866db5e9d061a5481eea865ba7d8b94c

Sorry, wasn't' done typing :) I was going to suggest making one a D of the other but I guess it doesn't matter.  One other general comment though, instead of making iter_nodes behave 2 different ways, is there any downside to just always do the 'insert mode' thing and change the new parm to just shuffle=True/False?"}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-08-18 18:13:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Honestly, the whole reason for the indices was so that we don't have to change the behavior of iter_nodes() this much.

Currently, we've got the ring returning things in a particular order, then iter_nodes() reorders the primaries via a call to sort_nodes(). Also, there's the object controller's iter_nodes_local_first() that, if configured correctly, will yank handoffs ahead of primaries in the node chain. This patch doesn't handle that case; if write affinity is on, storage nodes will get wrong-index fragment archives on them.

Really, I prefer the index patch to this one; this patch leaks knowledge of EC all the way up into the proxy server; in a method that's used for every account, container, or object request; while the index one keeps EC stuff isolated to the object controller (and potentially to the storage policy object, depending on how we end up doing it.)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-18 18:39:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

commit_message:
Adding 'insert' mode in iter_nodes

By default iter_nodes will 'shift' nodes if there's failure happen.
With this patch it can insert handoff node to replace the failed
primary. This would save lots of data moving when the node rejoins the
cluster in EC reconstructor. Also disable sort_nodes to keep the
fragment archives' seqence the same as the node sequence in the ring.

Change-Id: I2f66fb17123a20f6d96bf0673af237efbc9e6e2e

commit_message:
Run dbsync commands with service user

In some cases these commands create log files, running them as the service
user prevents them being owned by root.

Change-Id: I5d5dc4b58f7fca494ac2617f15da9f90b5fa11c9

commit_message:
Remove the word 'More' in the row actions split button

The split button dropdown doesn't need the term 'More',
the caret icon is enough.  See bug report for example.
(It gives us more room for long primary button names like
'Edit Hosts Aggregate')

Change-Id: Ib789f9c5691cb0cec026ee8d877e6385315b00a7
Closes-Bug: #1357487

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-25 07:07:35.000000000', 'message': "Fixes silent deletion of environments

Now environment deletion is done as a regular deployment that can fail.
Environments that are deleted, but deletion process has failed remain in database
and shown in dashboard with status 'delete failure'. Environments that are being deleted
has status 'deleting' and do not disappear before they really got deleted on engine side

Also improved status reporting for environments. Now it also reports status of last deployment -
'deploy failure', 'delete failure'

Change-Id: I05625dd71f7ca9559bb88319b26b122214f15019
Closes-Bug: #1325101

commit_message:
Fixes silent deletion of environments

Now environment deletion is done as a regular deployment that can fail.
Environments that are deleted, but deletion process has failed remain in database
and shown in dashboard with status 'delete failure'. Environments that are being deleted
has status 'deleting' and do not disappear before they really got deleted on engine side

Also improved status reporting for environments. Now it also reports status of last deployment -
'deploy failure', 'delete failure'

P.S. Functional tests were slightly refactored and fixed to reflect changes
in deletion logic

Change-Id: I05625dd71f7ca9559bb88319b26b122214f15019
Closes-Bug: #1325101

commit_message:
Add disassocate_and_delete method for floatingip

In a previous patch: I53b0c9d949404288e8687b304361a74b53d69ef3
logic was added in nova.api.openstack.compute.contrib.floating_ips.\
FloatingIPController.delete() to special case the delete for neutron
so that it could be done atomically. This was done this way because we
needed to backport that and did not want to introduce a new network_api in
a backport. This patch adds a new network_api disassocate_and_delete
which allows us to remove this hackery in the api layer.

Change-Id: I11c7cdd03549b11d57f2e3567a96611b28b77df3
Related-bug: 1356157
Closes-bug: 1356583

commit_message:
Separating Identity Dashboard and using RBAC

Moving identity panels to their own dashboard.

RBAC is now used to determine the data to load in the identity
dashboard. Using the default policy file, a user with role member
will now be able to see their project list.

Also, adding a policy check mechanism at the panel and dashboard
level to determine which panels and dashboards the user can access.

Implements blueprint separate-identity-dash

Change-Id: I7ebfec2bf6e44899bec79d3b23c90d56a976200f

commit_message:
cron job to clean up rabbitmq connections

Install a cleanup script to terminate RabbitMQ connections that don't
have any channels, set up a cron job to run the script every minute.

Change-Id: I1d9e79a9ef28076f83dd9426d17de7d8d4b97d30
Related-Bug: #856764

[{'created': '2014-08-17 12:07:07.000000000', 'message': 'User internalURL for interaction with volume api

Currently nova compute uses publicURLs for communication with
cinder api. This prevents from removing public ips from compute nodes

- Add cinder_catalog_option to nova::compute class
- Set default cinder_catalog_option to internalURL in openstack/all.pp

Change-Id: I122d04221eedaa9667f396b2494573804a8abd66
Closes-Bug: 1357292
'}, {'created': '2014-08-17 14:02:09.000000000', 'message': 'User internalURL for interaction with volume api

Currently nova compute uses publicURLs for communication with
cinder api. This prevents from removing public ips from compute nodes

- Add additional params to nova_config,
  cinder_catalog_option=volume.cinder.internalURL

Change-Id: I122d04221eedaa9667f396b2494573804a8abd66
Closes-Bug: 1357292
'}]
commit_message:
User internalURL for interaction with volume api

Currently nova compute uses publicURLs for communication with
cinder api. This prevents from removing public ips from compute nodes

- Add additional params to nova_config,
  cinder_catalog_option=volume.cinder.internalURL

Change-Id: I122d04221eedaa9667f396b2494573804a8abd66
Closes-Bug: 1357292

[{'created': '2014-08-05 19:12:43.000000000', 'message': 'Add MatchesDictExceptForKeys custom matcher

Add a custom matcher that compares two dictionaries, except for
keys matching an exclusion list.
The matcher returns with a mismatch object design to provide a
useful message in case of failed assertion, which pinpoints the
differences between the two dicts.

Verified via unit tests.

commit_message:
Add MatchesDictExceptForKeys custom matcher

Add a custom matcher that compares two dictionaries, except for
keys matching an exclusion list.
The matcher returns with a mismatch object design to provide a
useful message in case of failed assertion, which pinpoints the
differences between the two dicts.

Verified via unit tests.

Partially implements: bp/tempest-client-scenarios

Change-Id: Ibdd34fa1f095ee2ee33e11a8e23e654fb6d12b89

This makes the virt.firewall code cleaner in terms of referencing
the cached instance and network_info code it stores. Before this
patch, concurrent instance operations could modify these two dicts
so that while we're iterating instances, the network_info dict
is suddenly missing information we need.

The right fix for this is to use instance objects and their
associated info_cache objects, but that's a larger fix and one
not as well-suited to backporting to previous releases which
suffer from this as well.

The approach taken here is that we store the instance and
network_info cache together in the same dict that we can pop()
from atomically (this is not really necessary, but helps to
prevent introducing more of these cases). When we iterate over

not to let a suddenly-missing key break us, and passing the

hit the cache dicts again.

commit_message:
Avoid referencing stale instance/network_info dicts in firewall

This makes the virt.firewall code cleaner in terms of referencing
the cached instance and network_info code it stores. Before this
patch, concurrent instance operations could modify these two dicts
so that while we're iterating instances, the network_info dict
is suddenly missing information we need.

The right fix for this is to use instance objects and their
associated info_cache objects, but that's a larger fix and one
not as well-suited to backporting to previous releases which
suffer from this as well.

The approach taken here is that we store the instance and
network_info cache together in the same dict that we can pop()
from atomically (this is not really necessary, but helps to
prevent introducing more of these cases). When we iterate over
the contents, we iterate over a copy of the keys, being careful
not to let a suddenly-missing key break us, and passing the
details all the way down the stack instead of having deeper calls
hit the cache dicts again.

Conflicts:
	nova/virt/firewall.py

Change-Id: Ib1cfd68fca7789ca4a3602c25e6b8a956303fff9
Closes-bug: #1182131
(cherry picked from commit 72dd81343e73baf838bc58d413413f0d57018f15)

commit_message:
Add documentation for cinder volume encryption.

Closes-Bug: #1224977

Documentation covers the setup of encryption configuration,
creating the necessary volume-type and creating encrypted
volumes.  Also shows a short procedure to validate encryption.

Change-Id: I58b84e5119f56873fd4b74949d42f013b07ec91d

commit_message:
Support environments being deleted of with delete failure

Correctly display environments that has deletion going on
or had failed during that process (and thus remained in the list)

Also adds support for new environment statuses

This is a dashboard supplement to https://review.openstack.org/109508
and should be merged be merged *BEFORE* API change

Change-Id: I7ddb9828f584274f93427d03b53e571d591f0097

commit_message:
Refactor ssh actions used for node erasing

Patch fixes few issues with erasing drives while
stopping deployment during provisioning, e.g.:
 * executing dd with non-existing under
   debootstrap shell option 'flag';
 * broken check of block device major code;
 * incorrect order of arguments, which are passed
   to erase_data function;
Also it implements more robust mechanizm to detect
provisining or provisined node.

Change-Id: Ic6022cc4ecb405a17dbeefb095590532cbbbe33b
Related-bug: #1316583
(cherry picked from commit 4bf5312f4752769b51974ee5804dd224b67a0dcf)

commit_message:
Zaqar is depending on python-keystoneclient

Zaqar is taking keystonemiddleware as dependency, but when install
keystonemiddleware, keystoneclient won't be installed automatically.
So we need to make sure python-keystoneclient in the requirements.txt.

Change-Id: I2f8523e6971d4f2f450ada02fec96fb178bde87b
Closes-Bug: 1358262

Fix client exception handling in VolumeExtendTask

This class was not ported correctly to use new is_client_exception
method of client_plugin.

commit_message:
Adds barbican keymgr wrapper

Adds a barbican keymgr wrapper to the key manager interface in
cinder.  This allows barbican to be configured as the key manager
for encryption keys in cinder.  The wrapper translates calls from
the existing key manager interface to python-barbicanclient.

There are two new configuration variables: encryption_auth_url
(the authentication URL for the encryption service) and
encryption_api_url (the api URL for the encryption service).

Change-Id: Ifd0d9b073d7f1c3c92d318c20a080b253008b50c
Implements: blueprint encryption-with-barbican
DocImpact

[{'created': '2014-07-24 14:36:24.000000000', 'message': 'Fixed --debug option printing malformed URLs

Fixing minor bug causing log_curl_request method to print malformed
URLs for curl commands. log_curl_request is used for debug mode.

Change-Id: Ic6c58ba7f93cee20d3ad2d0cb84f6e56901aa9a5

commit_message:
Fixed --debug option printing malformed URLs

Fixing minor bug causing log_curl_request method to print malformed
URLs for curl commands. log_curl_request is used for debug mode.

Change-Id: Ic6c58ba7f93cee20d3ad2d0cb84f6e56901aa9a5
Closes-Bug: 1348205

commit_message:
Remove INACTIVE status from FWaaS

DOWN status is introduced to replace INACTIVE status. There is one
place in FWaaS code which still checks INACTIVE status.

This commit removes INACTIVE status from FWaaS.

Change-Id: I896c81a6229978a46f8a88a31936920a1036f142
Partial-Bug: #1286048

commit_message:
Move DevStack to QA program

The DevStack project moves to QA and the DevStack program
moves to /dev/null.

Change-Id: I42cdbb8dbbc98a3d83b6bb1abcaadefcc0618bb8

[{'created': '2014-08-18 19:08:53.000000000', 'message': 'Add owner_id to new _create_stack RPC interface

Adds a new "internal" _create_stack RPC call, which exposes a superset
of the existing RPC interfaces, intended only for engine-to-engine
usage, not for exposure via the user-facing API's (hence the prefix)

This patch exposes "owner_id" via the new call, which enables creation
of nested stacks via an RPC call, instead of creating the stack directly.

Change-Id: I355c608e657cb9dae2d2b38658b0b247040de6b9
blueprint: decouple-nested
'}]
commit_message:
Add owner_id to new _create_stack RPC interface

Adds a new "internal" _create_stack RPC call, which exposes a superset
of the existing RPC interfaces, intended only for engine-to-engine
usage, not for exposure via the user-facing API's (hence the prefix)

This patch exposes "owner_id" via the new call, which enables creation
of nested stacks via an RPC call, instead of creating the stack directly.

Change-Id: I355c608e657cb9dae2d2b38658b0b247040de6b9
blueprint: decouple-nested

commit_message:
Return metadata from resource_signal RPC interface

To enable us to completely remove the metadata_update call without
breaking the current CFN waitcondition API, we need to return the
resource metadata, like metadata_update does (currently we don't
return anything when handling a signal).  This should not be
expensive as the metadata has just been updated, thus should be
cached inside the resource object.

Change-Id: I29bf6f9f5fab133b06ab8ecc92d7556a9bb6e35a

commit_message:
Using default FnGetRefId behavior for LaunchConfig

FnGetRefId of LaunchConfig returns only physical_resource_name, but in
the case where a resource is not created, resource.id equals None. So the
result of FnGetRefId will be None too. It gives unpredictable behavior
during preview, when other resources return None too.

Change-Id: I425f777dbd0600e35354b0d5308cdaf701d85119
Closes-Bug: #1324493

Fix a number of small things to support Python 2.6, Python 2.7 as
well as Python 3.3.

Change-Id: I213c847c93cfe3d7f1fd8c8ea4709b7980fd52f9

Hi Thomas,

Unittests are expected to be used either via tox or via run_tests.

To run one particular module you can use following:

"$ ./run_tests.sh manila.tests.test_share_generic"

Nosetests are not 'supported' and if try each module separately, I think there will be much more such "not found" opts.

Also, LVM driver is expected to be removed, see: https://review.openstack.org/112040 , hence its opt 'share_export_ip' will be removed.'}, {'account_id': 7102, 'date': '2014-08-16 07:40:23.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

commit_message:
Handle missing config options for tests gracefully

Running a subset of testcases (i.e. with "run_tests.sh -d
manila.tests.test_share_generic") leads to NoSuchOptError. Just ignore
tthis error and assume that the option is not needed because it's not
imported.

Co-Authored-By: Valeriy Ponomaryov <vponomaryov@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: Ib739452b139d9c2d7302c4a06336787890c50bb1

multiple statements in one call to .execute():

> InterfaceError: (InterfaceError) Use multi=True when executing
> multiple statements

Split statements and execute one by one.

blueprint switch-to-mysql-connector

'}, {'created': '2014-08-14 09:06:06.000000000', 'message': 'migration: adopt for MySQL Connector

For MySQL Connector, we get the following error when trying to execute
multiple statements in one call to .execute():

> InterfaceError: (InterfaceError) Use multi=True when executing
> multiple statements

Split statements and execute one by one.

commit_message:
migration: adopt for MySQL Connector

For MySQL Connector, we get the following error when trying to execute
multiple statements in one call to .execute():

> InterfaceError: (InterfaceError) Use multi=True when executing
> multiple statements

Split statements and execute one by one.

blueprint enable-mysql-connector

Change-Id: I9850e12f88ff44e85925082c5f71c5b75a4dee69

commit_message:
Skip FWaaS config mismatch check if RPC method is unsupported

In this commit FWaaS config check skip is skipped
if neutron server does not support this API.

Commit d6f014d introduced FWaaS config mismatch check between
server and agent. It added a new RPC method get_service_plugin_list
and bumped l3-agent RPC version to 1.3, but this version RPC is
only supported by L3 router service plugin and
it breaks existing plugins using L3 router mixin.

Bumping l3-agent RPC version requires detailed investigation on all
affected plugins and it can be done by plugin maintainer later.

Change-Id: I388a24b0c6a507203674ef108bb14cea0534f98c
Closes-Bug: #1353309

commit_message:
This fix cancel sensitivities to '/' in the end of 'urls of nsx bits' which may be reason of failed deploy for neutron with NSX.

Also level of log messages changed to error when puppet can not download packages for correct work nsx.

Closes-Bug: #1356294

Change-Id: Ifce55943876d87ced49c9160f6b812ab71999341

commit_message:
Do not create an empty directory 'pseudo/'

This is a fix-up for the commit 3d56b65c. The code change was good,
but the additional test had a side effect of creating an empty
directory "pseudo/". Fix this by mocking-out mkdirs().

Change-Id: Iead55e72d8a75d96bde0a7491aca12bbdcc269cf

commit_message:
Fix output/doc strings that assume only XML files

Doctest checks not only XML files, but doc strings and output still give
that impression. To avoid confusion among users and code readers, this
patch updates said strings.

Change-Id: Ifee1f79ade743c53cb9e0966ad244002d6306fb8

DO NOT APPROVE: Demo tiny jobs and failures

The syntax check has been enhanced to combine syntax, niceness and
deletions check. Each of these three will fail due to the other changes.
Please check whether this works.

For details see
https://review.openstack.org/113133

DO NOT APPROVE THIS PATCH!

commit_message:
labs: set tunnel IP address

Replace placeholder INSTANCE_TUNNELS_INTERFACE_IP_ADDRESS with the
node's IP address in the data network.

To that end, the patch adds a new function hostname_to_ip.

Change-Id: I7baabdde50e62c9c8f006c19eddeca54d368666b
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs

commit_message:
Enforce image_size_cap on v2 upload

image_size_cap should be checked and enforced on upload

Enforcement is in two places:
- on image metadata save
- during image save to backend store

Closes-Bug: 1315321
Change-Id: I45bfb360703617bc394e9e27fe17adf43b09c0e1
Co-Author: Manuel Desbonnet <manuel.desbonnet@hp.com>

commit_message:
neutronv2: treat instance like object in allocate_for_instance

The allocate_for_instance method gets an instance object from the
compute manager so treat it like an object by using dot notation.

Updates the existing unit tests to use an instance object.

Part of blueprint compute-manager-objects-juno

Change-Id: Ia9305a67d1b9bd8601443da3288f710ab02b3f37

commit_message:
Add tests which check task dependencies

- Added new test file with tests which check workflow execution and
task dependencies.
- Update base.py file, rename '_create_execution' method, make it more
common
- Refactor tests in the test_mistral_base file according method remaning
- Change test workflow demo.yaml

Targets blueprint: mistral-workflow-execution-tests

Change-Id: If58d9d0da8a7204214f92fdb12ed87cb1801c17b

[{'created': '2014-08-16 01:06:58.000000000', 'message': 'If not provided create and populate a in-memory backend

To allow for moving from a dumb backend model to a backend
persistence model that can provide storage backends in a smart
manner we need to ensure and engine always has a backend even
if one was not provided so that we can let the backend provide
the most appropriate storage implementation.

Part of blueprint lb-not-collections

Breaking change: removes storage.SingleThreadedStorage and
storage.MultiThreadedStorage as now *all* backends are expected
to provide storage objects which work in threaded or non-threaded
setups.

Change-Id: I11fe0fbe8b71927b74994e4deb77374a30b928b3
'}]
commit_message:
If not provided create and populate a in-memory backend

To allow for moving from a dumb backend model to a backend
persistence model that can provide storage backends in a smart
manner we need to ensure and engine always has a backend even
if one was not provided so that we can let the backend provide
the most appropriate storage implementation.

Part of blueprint lb-not-collections

Breaking change: removes storage.SingleThreadedStorage and
storage.MultiThreadedStorage as now *all* backends are expected
to provide storage objects which work in threaded or non-threaded
setups.

commit_message:
Revert "Remove ESXDriver from Juno."

This commit looks like it broke the vmware virt driver so reverting
it for now as a defensive move until we can figure out why it isn't
working anymore.

This reverts commit 1deb31f85a8f5d1e261b2cf1eddc537a5da7f60b.

Change-Id: I267de125fcb4ce786c7d3b63a589d31d07eb6c1d
